# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectroscopy-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy is employed as an analytical chemistry tool to determine the presence of a particular substance in a sample and, in many cases, to quantify the amount of the substance present.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Infrared and ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy are particularly common in analytical applications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in studies of molecular and atomic physics, astronomical spectroscopy and remote sensing.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] There is a wide range of experimental approaches for measuring absorption spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The most common arrangement is to direct a generated beam of radiation at a sample and detect the intensity of the radiation that passes through it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The transmitted energy can be used to calculate the absorption.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The source, sample arrangement and detection technique vary significantly depending on the frequency range and the purpose of the experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] A material's absorption spectrum is the fraction of incident radiation absorbed by the material over a range of frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The absorption spectrum is primarily determined by the atomic and molecular composition of the material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Radiation is more likely to be absorbed at frequencies that match the energy difference between two quantum mechanical states of the molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The absorption that occurs due to a transition between two states is referred to as an absorption line and a spectrum is typically composed of many lines.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The frequencies at which absorption lines occur, as well as their relative intensities, primarily depend on the electronic and molecular structure of the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The frequencies will also depend on the interactions between molecules in the sample, the crystal structure in solids, and on several environmental factors (e.g., temperature, pressure, electric field, magnetic field).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The lines will also have a width and shape that are primarily determined by the spectral density or the density of states of the system.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption lines are typically classified by the nature of the quantum mechanical change induced in the molecule or atom.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Rotational lines, for instance, occur when the rotational state of a molecule is changed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Rotational lines are typically found in the microwave spectral region.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Vibrational lines correspond to changes in the vibrational state of the molecule and are typically found in the infrared region.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Electronic lines correspond to a change in the electronic state of an atom or molecule and are typically found in the visible and ultraviolet region.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] X-ray absorptions are associated with the excitation of inner shell electrons in atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] These changes can also be combined (e.g. rotation–vibration transitions), leading to new absorption lines at the combined energy of the two changes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The energy associated with the quantum mechanical change primarily determines the frequency of the absorption line but the frequency can be shifted by several types of interactions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Electric and magnetic fields can cause a shift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Interactions with neighboring molecules can cause shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For instance, absorption lines of the gas phase molecule can shift significantly when that molecule is in a liquid or solid phase and interacting more strongly with neighboring molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The width and shape of absorption lines are determined by the instrument used for the observation, the material absorbing the radiation and the physical environment of that material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] It is common for lines to have the shape of a Gaussian or Lorentzian distribution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] It is also common for a line to be described solely by its intensity and width instead of the entire shape being characterized.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The integrated intensity—obtained by integrating the area under the absorption line—is proportional to the amount of the absorbing substance present.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The intensity is also related to the temperature of the substance and the quantum mechanical interaction between the radiation and the absorber.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] This interaction is quantified by the transition moment and depends on the particular lower state the transition starts from, and the upper state it is connected to.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The width of absorption lines may be determined by the spectrometer used to record it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] A spectrometer has an inherent limit on how narrow a line it can resolve and so the observed width may be at this limit.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] If the width is larger than the resolution limit, then it is primarily determined by the environment of the absorber.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] A liquid or solid absorber, in which neighboring molecules strongly interact with one another, tends to have broader absorption lines than a gas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Increasing the temperature or pressure of the absorbing material will also tend to increase the line width.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] It is also common for several neighboring transitions to be close enough to one another that their lines overlap and the resulting overall line is therefore broader yet.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption and transmission spectra represent equivalent information and one can be calculated from the other through a mathematical transformation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] A transmission spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is weakest because more light is transmitted through the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] An absorption spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is strongest.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Emission is a process by which a substance releases energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Emission can occur at any frequency at which absorption can occur, and this allows the absorption lines to be determined from an emission spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The emission spectrum will typically have a quite different intensity pattern from the absorption spectrum, though, so the two are not equivalent.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The absorption spectrum can be calculated from the emission spectrum using Einstein coefficients.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The scattering and reflection spectra of a material are influenced by both its refractive index and its absorption spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] In an optical context, the absorption spectrum is typically quantified by the extinction coefficient, and the extinction and index coefficients are quantitatively related through the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Therefore, the absorption spectrum can be derived from a scattering or reflection spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] This typically requires simplifying assumptions or models, and so the derived absorption spectrum is an approximation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy is useful in chemical analysis because of its specificity and its quantitative nature.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The specificity of absorption spectra allows compounds to be distinguished from one another in a mixture, making absorption spectroscopy useful in wide variety of applications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For instance, Infrared gas analyzers can be used to detect pollutants in the air, distinguishing them from nitrogen, oxygen, water, and other expected constituents.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The specificity also allows unknown samples to be identified by comparing a measured spectrum with a library of reference spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] In many cases, qualitative information about a sample can be determined even if it is not in a library.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Infrared spectra, for instance, have characteristic absorption bands that indicate if carbon-hydrogen or carbon-oxygen bonds are present.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] An absorption spectrum can be quantitatively related to the amount of material present using the Beer–Lambert law .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Determining the absolute concentration of a compound requires knowledge of the compound's absorption coefficient.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The absorption coefficient for some compounds is available in reference sources, and it can also be determined by measuring the spectrum of a calibration standard with a known concentration of the target compound.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] One of the unique advantages of spectroscopy as an analytical technique is that measurements can be made without bringing the instrument and sample into contact.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Radiation that travels between a sample and an instrument will contain the spectral information, so the measurement can be made remotely.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Remote spectral sensing is valuable in many situations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For example, measurements can be made in toxic or hazardous environments without placing an operator or instrument at risk.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Also, sample material does not have to be brought into contact with the instrument—preventing possible cross contamination.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Remote spectral measurements present several challenges compared to laboratory measurements.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The space in between the sample of interest and the instrument may also have spectral absorptions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] These absorptions can mask or confound the absorption spectrum of the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] These background interferences may also vary over time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The source of radiation in remote measurements is often an environmental source, such as sunlight or the thermal radiation from a warm object, and this makes it necessary to distinguish spectral absorption from changes in the source spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] To simplify these challenges, differential optical absorption spectroscopy has gained some popularity, as it focusses on differential absorption features and omits broad-band absorption such as aerosol extinction and extinction due to rayleigh scattering.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] This method is applied to ground-based, airborne, and satellite-based measurements.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Some ground-based methods provide the possibility to retrieve tropospheric and stratospheric trace gas profiles.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Astronomical spectroscopy is a particularly significant type of remote spectral sensing.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] In this case, the objects and samples of interest are so distant from earth that electromagnetic radiation is the only means available to measure them.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Astronomical spectra contain both absorption and emission spectral information.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy has been particularly important for understanding interstellar clouds and determining that some of them contain molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in the study of extrasolar planets.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Detection of extrasolar planets by transit photometry also measures their absorption spectrum and allows for the determination of the planet's atmospheric composition, temperature, pressure, and scale height, and hence allows also for the determination of the planet's mass.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Theoretical models, principally quantum mechanical models, allow for the absorption spectra of atoms and molecules to be related to other physical properties such as electronic structure, atomic or molecular mass, and molecular geometry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Therefore, measurements of the absorption spectrum are used to determine these other properties.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Microwave spectroscopy, for example, allows for the determination of bond lengths and angles with high precision.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] In addition, spectral measurements can be used to determine the accuracy of theoretical predictions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For example, the Lamb shift measured in the hydrogen atomic absorption spectrum was not expected to exist at the time it was measured.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Its discovery spurred and guided the development of quantum electrodynamics, and measurements of the Lamb shift are now used to determine the fine-structure constant.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The most straightforward approach to absorption spectroscopy is to generate radiation with a source, measure a reference spectrum of that radiation with a detector and then re-measure the sample spectrum after placing the material of interest in between the source and detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The two measured spectra can then be combined to determine the material's absorption spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The reference spectrum will be affected in the same way, though, by these experimental conditions and therefore the combination yields the absorption spectrum of the material alone.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] A wide variety of radiation sources are employed in order to cover the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For spectroscopy, it is generally desirable for a source to cover a broad swath of wavelengths in order to measure a broad region of the absorption spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Some sources inherently emit a broad spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Examples of these include globars or other black body sources in the infrared, mercury lamps in the visible and ultraviolet, and X-ray tubes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] One recently developed, novel source of broad spectrum radiation is synchrotron radiation, which covers all of these spectral regions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Other radiation sources generate a narrow spectrum, but the emission wavelength can be tuned to cover a spectral range.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Examples of these include klystrons in the microwave region and lasers across the infrared, visible, and ultraviolet region (though not all lasers have tunable wavelengths).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The detector employed to measure the radiation power will also depend on the wavelength range of interest.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Most detectors are sensitive to a fairly broad spectral range and the sensor selected will often depend more on the sensitivity and noise requirements of a given measurement.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Examples of detectors common in spectroscopy include heterodyne receivers in the microwave, bolometers in the millimeter-wave and infrared, mercury cadmium telluride and other cooled semiconductor detectors in the infrared, and photodiodes and photomultiplier tubes in the visible and ultraviolet.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] If both the source and the detector cover a broad spectral region, then it is also necessary to introduce a means of resolving the wavelength of the radiation in order to determine the spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Often a spectrograph is used to spatially separate the wavelengths of radiation so that the power at each wavelength can be measured independently.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] It is also common to employ interferometry to determine the spectrum—Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy is a widely used implementation of this technique.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] Two other issues that must be considered in setting up an absorption spectroscopy experiment include the optics used to direct the radiation and the means of holding or containing the sample material (called a cuvette or cell).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For most UV, visible, and NIR measurements the use of precision quartz cuvettes are necessary.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] In both cases, it is important to select materials that have relatively little absorption of their own in the wavelength range of interest.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] The absorption of other materials could interfere with or mask the absorption from the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/absorption-spectroscopy] For instance, in several wavelength ranges it is necessary to measure the sample under vacuum or in a noble gas environment because gases in the atmosphere have interfering absorption features.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The **emission spectrum** of a chemical element or chemical compound is the spectrum of frequencies of electromagnetic radiation emitted due to electrons making a transition from a high energy state to a lower energy state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The photon energy of the emitted photons is equal to the energy difference between the two states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] There are many possible electron transitions for each atom, and each transition has a specific energy difference.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This collection of different transitions, leading to different radiated wavelengths, make up an emission spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Each element's emission spectrum is unique.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Therefore, spectroscopy can be used to identify elements in matter of unknown composition.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Similarly, the emission spectra of molecules can be used in chemical analysis of substances.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In physics, emission is the process by which a higher energy quantum mechanical state of a particle becomes converted to a lower one through the emission of a photon, resulting in the production of light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The frequency of light emitted is a function of the energy of the transition.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Since energy must be conserved, the energy difference between the two states equals the energy carried off by the photon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The energy states of the transitions can lead to emissions over a very large range of frequencies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] For example, visible light is emitted by the coupling of electronic states in atoms and molecules (then the phenomenon is called fluorescence or phosphorescence).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] On the other hand, nuclear shell transitions can emit high energy gamma rays, while nuclear spin transitions emit low energy radio waves.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The emittance of an object quantifies how much light is emitted by it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This may be related to other properties of the object through the Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] For most substances, the amount of emission varies with the temperature and the spectroscopic composition of the object, leading to the appearance of color temperature and emission lines.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Precise measurements at many wavelengths allow the identification of a substance via emission spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The quantum mechanics problem is treated using time-dependent perturbation theory and leads to the general result known as Fermi's golden rule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The description has been superseded by quantum electrodynamics, although the semi-classical version continues to be more useful in most practical computations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] When the electrons in the atom are excited, for example by being heated, the additional energy pushes the electrons to higher energy orbitals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] When the electrons fall back down and leave the excited state, energy is re-emitted in the form of a photon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The wavelength (or equivalently, frequency) of the photon is determined by the difference in energy between the two states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] These emitted photons form the element's spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The fact that only certain colors appear in an element's atomic emission spectrum means that only certain frequencies of light are emitted.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Each of these frequencies are related to energy by the formula: $E_{\text{photon}}=h\nu ,$ where $E_{\text{photon}}$ is the energy of the photon, $\nu$ is its frequency, and h is the Planck constant.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This concludes that only photons with specific energies are emitted by the atom.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The principle of the atomic emission spectrum explains the varied colors in neon signs, as well as chemical flame test results (described below).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The frequencies of light that an atom can emit are dependent on states the electrons can be in.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] When excited, an electron moves to a higher energy level or orbital.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] When the electron falls back to its ground level the light is emitted.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The above picture shows the visible light emission spectrum for hydrogen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] If only a single atom of hydrogen were present, then only a single wavelength would be observed at a given instant.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Several of the possible emissions are observed because the sample contains many hydrogen atoms that are in different initial energy states and reach different final energy states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] These different combinations lead to simultaneous emissions at different wavelengths.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] As well as the electronic transitions discussed above, the energy of a molecule can also change via rotational, vibrational, and vibronic (combined vibrational and electronic) transitions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] These energy transitions often lead to closely spaced groups of many different spectral lines, known as spectral bands.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Unresolved band spectra may appear as a spectral continuum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Light consists of electromagnetic radiation of different wavelengths.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Therefore, when the elements or their compounds are heated either on a flame or by an electric arc they emit energy in the form of light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Analysis of this light, with the help of a spectroscope gives us a discontinuous spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] A spectroscope or a spectrometer is an instrument which is used for separating the components of light, which have different wavelengths.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The spectrum appears in a series of lines called the line spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This line spectrum is called an atomic spectrum when it originates from an atom in elemental form.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Each element has a different atomic spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The production of line spectra by the atoms of an element indicate that an atom can radiate only a certain amount of energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This leads to the conclusion that bound electrons cannot have just any amount of energy but only a certain, specific amount of energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The emission spectrum can be used to determine the composition of a material, since it is different for each element of the periodic table.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] One example is astronomical spectroscopy: identifying the composition of stars by analysing the received light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The emission spectrum characteristics of some elements are plainly visible to the naked eye when these elements are heated.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] For example, when platinum wire is dipped into a sodium nitrate solution and then inserted into a flame, the sodium atoms emit an amber yellow color.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Similarly, when indium is inserted into a flame, the flame becomes blue.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] These definite characteristics allow elements to be identified by their atomic emission spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Not all emitted lights are perceptible to the naked eye, as the spectrum also includes ultraviolet rays and infrared radiation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] An emission spectrum is formed when an excited gas is viewed directly through a spectroscope.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] There are many ways in which atoms can be brought to an excited state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Interaction with electromagnetic radiation is used in fluorescence spectroscopy, protons or other heavier particles in particle-induced X-ray emission and electrons or X-ray photons in energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy or X-ray fluorescence.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The simplest method is to heat the sample to a high temperature, after which the excitations are produced by collisions between the sample atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This method is used in flame emission spectroscopy, and it was also the method used by Anders Jonas Ångström when he discovered the phenomenon of discrete emission lines in the 1850s.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Although the emission lines are caused by a transition between quantized energy states and may at first look very sharp, they do have a finite width, i.e. they are composed of more than one wavelength of light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This spectral line broadening has many different causes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Emission spectroscopy is often referred to as optical emission spectroscopy because of the light nature of what is being emitted.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In 1756 Thomas Melvill observed the emission of distinct patterns of colour when salts were added to alcohol flames.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] By 1785 James Gregory discovered the principles of diffraction grating and American astronomer David Rittenhouse made the first engineered diffraction grating.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In 1821 Joseph von Fraunhofer solidified this significant experimental leap of replacing a prism as the source of wavelength dispersion improving the spectral resolution and allowing for the dispersed wavelengths to be quantified.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In 1835, Charles Wheatstone reported that different metals could be distinguished by bright lines in the emission spectra of their sparks, thereby introducing an alternative to flame spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Foucault experimentally demonstrated that absorption and emission lines at the same wavelength are both due to the same material, with the difference between the two originating from the temperature of the light source.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In 1853, the Swedish physicist Anders Jonas Ångström presented observations and theories about gas spectra. Ångström postulated that an incandescent gas emits luminous rays of the same wavelength as those it can absorb.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] At the same time George Stokes and William Thomson (Kelvin) were discussing similar postulates. Ångström also measured the emission spectrum from hydrogen later labeled the Balmer lines.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In 1854 and 1855, David Alter published observations on the spectra of metals and gases, including an independent observation of the Balmer lines of hydrogen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] By 1859, Gustav Kirchhoff and Robert Bunsen noticed that several Fraunhofer lines (lines in the solar spectrum) coincide with characteristic emission lines identified in the spectra of heated elements.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] It was correctly deduced that dark lines in the solar spectrum are caused by absorption by chemical elements in the solar atmosphere.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The solution containing the relevant substance to be analysed is drawn into the burner and dispersed into the flame as a fine spray.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The solvent evaporates first, leaving finely divided solid particles which move to the hottest region of the flame where gaseous atoms and ions are produced through the dissociation of molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Here electrons are excited as described above, and the spontaneously emit photon to decay to lower energy states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] It is common for a monochromator to be used to allow for easy detection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] On a simple level, flame emission spectroscopy can be observed using just a flame and samples of metal salts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This method of qualitative analysis is called a flame test.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] For example, sodium salts placed in the flame will glow yellow from sodium ions, while strontium (used in road flares) ions color it red.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] Copper wire will create a green colored flame, however in the presence of chloride gives blue (molecular contribution by CuCl).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] In Thomson scattering a charged particle emits radiation under incident light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The particle may be an ordinary atomic electron, so emission coefficients have practical applications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] If ***X*** *dV* *d*Ω *dλ* is the energy scattered by a volume element *dV* into solid angle *d*Ω between wavelengths λ and *λ* + *dλ* per unit time then the emission coefficient is ***X***.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] The values of ***X*** in Thomson scattering can be predicted from incident flux, the density of the charged particles and their Thomson differential cross section (area/solid angle).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] A warm body emitting photons has a monochromatic emission coefficient relating to its temperature and total power radiation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/emission-spectrum] This is sometimes called the second Einstein coefficient, and can be deduced from quantum mechanical theory.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a typical MS procedure, a sample, which may be solid, liquid, or gaseous, is ionized, for example by bombarding it with a beam of electrons.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This may cause some of the sample's molecules to break up into positively charged fragments or simply become positively charged without fragmenting.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] These ions (fragments) are then separated according to their mass-to-charge ratio, for example by accelerating them and subjecting them to an electric or magnetic field: ions of the same mass-to-charge ratio will undergo the same amount of deflection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions are detected by a mechanism capable of detecting charged particles, such as an electron multiplier.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Results are displayed as spectra of the signal intensity of detected ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The atoms or molecules in the sample can be identified by correlating known masses (e.g. an entire molecule) to the identified masses or through a characteristic fragmentation pattern.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1886, Eugen Goldstein observed rays in gas discharges under low pressure that traveled away from the anode and through channels in a perforated cathode, opposite to the direction of negatively charged cathode rays (which travel from cathode to anode).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Goldstein called these positively charged anode rays "Kanalstrahlen"; the standard translation of this term into English is "canal rays".
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wilhelm Wien found that strong electric or magnetic fields deflected the canal rays and, in 1899, constructed a device with perpendicular electric and magnetic fields that separated the positive rays according to their charge-to-mass ratio (*Q/m*).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wien found that the charge-to-mass ratio depended on the nature of the gas in the discharge tube.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thomson later improved on the work of Wien by reducing the pressure to create the mass spectrograph.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The word *spectrograph* had become part of the international scientific vocabulary by 1884.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Early *spectrometry* devices that measured the mass-to-charge ratio of ions were called *mass spectrographs* which consisted of instruments that recorded a spectrum of mass values on a photographic plate.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A *mass spectroscope* is similar to a *mass spectrograph* except that the beam of ions is directed onto a phosphor screen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectroscope configuration was used in early instruments when it was desired that the effects of adjustments be quickly observed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Once the instrument was properly adjusted, a photographic plate was inserted and exposed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The term mass spectroscope continued to be used even though the direct illumination of a phosphor screen was replaced by indirect measurements with an oscilloscope.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The use of the term *mass spectroscopy* is now discouraged due to the possibility of confusion with light spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectrometry is often abbreviated as *mass-spec* or simply as *MS*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Modern techniques of mass spectrometry were devised by Arthur Jeffrey Dempster and F.W.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sector mass spectrometers known as calutrons were developed by Ernest O.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lawrence and used for separating the isotopes of uranium during the Manhattan Project.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Calutron mass spectrometers were used for uranium enrichment at the Oak Ridge, Tennessee Y-12 plant established during World War II.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1989, half of the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Hans Dehmelt and Wolfgang Paul for the development of the ion trap technique in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 2002, the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to John Bennett Fenn for the development of electrospray ionization (ESI) and Koichi Tanaka for the development of soft laser desorption and their application to the ionization of biological macromolecules, especially proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectrometer consists of 5 components: **sample inlet**, **ion source** (or **ionizer**), **mass analyzer**, **detector**, data system.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each component can be varied somewhat independently from the other components, and the full mass spectrometer itself can be included as a component in an analysis pipeline, allowing great flexibility.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet prepares the sample to be analyzed in a suitable state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source takes samples from the sample inlet, converts a portion of the sample into a stream of ions, and outputs it to the mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There is a wide variety of ionization techniques, depending on the phase (solid, liquid, gas) of the sample and the efficiency of various ionization mechanisms for the unknown species.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] An extraction system removes ions from the sample, which are then targeted into the mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The mass analyzer takes an input stream of ions and separates ("analyzes") its constituent ions according to their *m/z*, the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector measures the value of an indicator quantity and thus provides data for calculating the abundances of each ion present.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some detectors also give spatial information, e.g., a multichannel plate.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The following describes the operation of a simple mass spectrometer that uses sector type.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consider a sample of sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In the ion source, the sample is vaporized (turned into gas) and ionized (transformed into electrically charged particles) into sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sodium atoms and ions are monoisotopic, with a mass of about 23 daltons (symbol: Da or older symbol: u).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Chloride atoms and ions come in two stable isotopes with masses of approximately 35 u (at a natural abundance of about 75 percent) and approximately 37 u (at a natural abundance of about 25 percent).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyzer part of the spectrometer contains electric and magnetic fields, which exert forces on ions traveling through these fields.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The speed of a charged particle may be increased or decreased while passing through the electric field, and its direction may be altered by the magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The magnitude of the deflection of the moving ion's trajectory depends on its mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lighter ions are deflected by the magnetic force to a greater degree than heavier ions (based on Newton's second law of motion, *F* = *ma*).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The streams of magnetically sorted ions pass from the analyzer to the detector, which records the relative abundance of each ion type.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This information is used to determine the chemical element composition of the original sample (i.e. that both sodium and chlorine are present in the sample) and the isotopic composition of its constituents (the ratio of 35Cl to 37Cl).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet provides a stream of neutral molecules, so that the ion source can ionize them.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The classical design produces the stream of molecules in the form of a low-pressure gas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is low-pressure, so that molecules within the stream does not frequently collide with each other.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions must travel without frequent collisions, because the instrument separates ions by their motion in electric and magnetic fields.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Despite being low-pressure, the sample stream is still at a much higher pressure than the rest of the system, which is held in a greater vacuum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the sample stream can only enter the ion source chamber via a small pinhole, called a **molecular leak**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample itself is already a gas, then the sample inlet can simply be a gas inlet with pressure valve.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is a volatile liquid or solid, then it can simply be placed in a chamber, vacuum-pumped to a low pressure.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is not sufficiently volatile, the sample inlet can be fitted within an oven.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is too nonvolatile to be turned into a low-pressure gas, then one can use a **direct probe**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The direct probe is a probe with a tip of thin wire loop, pin, or a capillary tube.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe is inserted through a vacuum lock into the ionization chamber, so that the tip is close to the ion source.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe can be heated to increase vapor pressure further.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such a system is effective for samples with vapor pressures lower than $10^{-9}$ mmHg at room temperature.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample can be prepared by an earlier analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, it can simply be the gaseous output of a gas chromatography machine as in GC-MS, or the liquid output of a high-performance liquid chromatography machine, as in HPLC-MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The recently developed "atmospheric pressure ionization" techniques allow us to entirely dispense with the sample inlet.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source is the part of the mass spectrometer that transforms the sample from the sample inlet into a stream of ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques with various dimensions for tradeoffs between different choices of ion sources, in terms of monetary cost, accuracy, precision, compatibility with other stages of spectroscopy, ease of use, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, EI is not suitable for coupling to HPLC, i.e.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] LC-MS, since at atmospheric pressure, the filaments used to generate electrons burn out rapidly.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus EI is coupled predominantly with GC, i.e.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] GC-MS, where the entire system is under high vacuum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two techniques often used with liquid and solid biological samples include electrospray ionization (invented by John Fenn) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI, initially developed as a similar technique Soft Laser Desorption) by K.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tanaka for which a Nobel Prize was awarded and as MALDI by M.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Hard ionization techniques are those that impart high quantities of residual internal energy in the subject molecule, even after ionization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Part of the energy would be dissipated by rupturing chemical bonds within the ion, producing many fragmentary radical ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The resultant ions tend to have *m/z* lower than the molecular ion (other than in the case of proton transfer and not including isotope peaks).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common example of hard ionization is electron ionization (EI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The radical ions produced after the first ionization are called second-generation product ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The products are then directed towards the mass analyzer by a repeller electrode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ionization process often follows predictable cleavage reactions that give rise to fragment ions which, following detection and signal processing, convey structural information about the analyte.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conversely, soft ionization techniques are those that impart little residual energy onto the subject molecule and as such result in little fragmentation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Examples include fast atom bombardment (FAB), chemical ionization (CI), atmospheric-pressure chemical ionization (APCI), atmospheric-pressure photoionization (APPI), electrospray ionization (ESI), desorption electrospray ionization (DESI), and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In electron ionization (EI), energetic electrons are produced by a hot cathode: a wire filament heated by running electric current through it, producing energetic electrons by thermionic emission.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrons are then accelerated towards an anode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The voltage difference between the cathode and the anode determines the energy of the electron stream.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Most organic compounds have ionization energy 8-15 eV, but empirically, the efficiency of ionization is too low unless the electron beam has an energy of 50-70 eV per electron.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The spectral features, including fragmentation patterns, depend on the energy setting.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conventionally for EI, the electron energy is standardized to be exactly 70 eV.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, if one wishes to compare their EI-MS results against standard databases, or produce results that can be added to standard databases, one must standardize their EI electron energy to 70 eV.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI accepts as input a stream of gas from the molecular leak.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The gas stream crosses the electron stream perpendicularly.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion stream then is accerelated by a succession of electrodes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically an ion carrying 1 e would be accelerated to 1-10 keV.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI has many benefits for routine mass spectrometry of small organic molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is cheap and robust, with reproducible spectrograms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Databases for EI spectrograms are widely available and covers many such molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI is unsuited for large molecules, such as most biomolecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a hard technique, which tends to break down large molecule ions during flight, since large molecules are particularly easy to fragment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Furthermore, large molecules are hard to volatilize without being degraded by heat.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In chemical ionization (CI), the analyte is ionized by a chemical reaction with an ionized reagent gas (itself ionized by some technique, such as by EI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyte gas and the reagent gas intersect, and react.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The reaction then produces ionized analyte fragments by various mechanisms, including proton transfer, electron transfer, and adduct formation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion is then accelerated electrostatically, as in EI.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] CI ion sources are similar to EI sources, and most modern mass spectrometers can switch from EI to CI mode in minutes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] To ensure efficiency, the amount of reagent is much higher than the analyte.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, a large amount of reagent ions would end up in the mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is usually handled by only measuring the part of the spectrogram with *m/z* above those of the main species in the reagent ion stream.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Common ionizing reagents for CI-MS include methane, ammonia, isobutane, and methanol.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The proton affinity of the reagent gas and of the sample should be matched to ensure efficient ionization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too high, ionization is inefficient.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too low, fragmentation is excessive.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Electrospray ionization (ESI) and thermospray ionization (TSI) are suited for high molecular weight biomolecules and other labile or nonvolatile compounds, and especially in a LC-MS system.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In both cases, the analyte is in a solution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solution is sprayed out, by either electrospraying or thermospraying, into a stream of mist, which then evaporates into an ion stream.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] TSI has been supplanted by ESI for most purposes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In TSI, the solution enters a heated capillary, producing a spray of droplets.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solvent evaporates, leaving ionized analytes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In ESI, the solution enters a capillary held at a high voltage (usually 2-5 kV), producing an electrospray into a heated chamber against a counterflow of a drying gas (usually nitrogen).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The charge density increases on a droplet as it evaporates, until the electrostatic energy overcomes the surface tension energy, exploding the droplet.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This process repeats, ending with an ion stream without the solvent.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Unlike in TSI, the analyte ions produced by ESI may carry a different amount of charge than the same analyte would carry in the solution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] That is, an analyte that is naturally occurring as M+ in the solution may end up becoming a stream of ions containing a mixture of M+, M2+, M3+, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical proteins can carry many protons due to the presence of basic amino acid side chains, resulting in peaks at *m/z* = 600–2000 for proteins with a molecular weight ~200,000 Da.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is convenient, since it means the ion would not exceed the *m/z* limits on typical mass analyzers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption ionization (DI) is a family of ionization techniques.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The main examples are secondary-ion mass spectrometry (SIMS), fast atom bombardment (FAB), and matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In DI, the sample is dissolved or dispersed in a matrix, and bombarded by a high-energy (1-10 keV) beam of ions (SIMS), neutral atoms (FAB), or photons (MALDI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The beam ionizes and expels (desorbs) some sample molecules off the matrix.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The matrix should be nonvolatile and relatively inert, so that it would not react with the analyte.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It should also be a good electrolyte to allow ion formation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ionized fragments of the matrix itself forms usually have $m/z\lesssim 600$ , so the spectrogram usually filters out that segment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] SIMS uses an ion beam, usually Ar+ or Cs+.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] FAB uses a neutral atom beam, usually Ar or Xe.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For SIMS and FAB, if the matrix compound is more acidic than the analyte, then predominantly (M + H)+ forms formed, and conversely (M − H)−.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Also possibly forming (M + Na)+, (M + K)+, etc, if the matrix is contaminated incidentally (adventitiously) by sodium, potassium, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical matrix materials include glycerol, thioglycerol, 3-nitrobenzyl alcohol, diethanolamine, triethanolamine, and dithiothreitol-dithioerythritol mixture.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are usually used to analyze polypeptides and oligonucleotides up to 20 kDa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE uses a photon beam, usually the soft-UV 337 nm nitrogen laser.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can also use an infrared (IR) laser for direct analysis of samples contained in gels or thin-layer chromatography (TLC) plates.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE can analyze small polymers (~1 kDa), to oligosaccharides, oligonucleotides and polypeptides, antibodies, up to small proteins (~300 kDa).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is highly sensitive, requiring only femtomoles of sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption/ionization on silicon (DIOS) is similar to MALDE, but without the matrix.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is deposited directly on a nanostructured (porous silicon) surface and the sample desorbed directly from the nanostructured surface through the adsorption of laser light energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] DIOS has been used to analyze organic molecules, metabolites, biomolecules and peptides, and, ultimately, to image tissues and cells.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Inductively coupled plasma (ICP) sources are used primarily for cation analysis of a wide array of sample types.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In this source, a plasma that is electrically neutral overall, but that has had a substantial fraction of its atoms ionized by high temperature, is used to atomize introduced sample molecules and to further strip the outer electrons from those atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The plasma is usually generated from argon gas, since the first ionization energy of argon atoms is higher than the first of any other elements except He, F and Ne, but lower than the second ionization energy of all except the most electropositive metals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The heating is achieved by a radio-frequency current passed through a coil surrounding the plasma.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Photoionization can be used in experiments which seek to use mass spectrometry as a means of resolving chemical kinetics mechanisms and isomeric product branching.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In such instances a high energy photon, either X-ray or uv, is used to dissociate stable gaseous molecules in a carrier gas of He or Ar.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In instances where a synchrotron light source is utilized, a tuneable photon energy can be utilized to acquire a photoionization efficiency curve which can be used in conjunction with the charge ratio *m/z* to fingerprint molecular and ionic species.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] More recently atmospheric pressure photoionization (APPI) has been developed to ionize molecules mostly as effluents of LC-MS systems.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some applications for ambient ionization include environmental applications as well as clinical applications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In these techniques, ions form in an ion source outside the mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sampling becomes easy as the samples don't need previous separation nor preparation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Others include glow discharge, field desorption (FD), spark ionization and thermal ionization (TIMS).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass analyzers separate the ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many types of mass analyzers, using either static or dynamic fields, magnetic or electric fields.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each analyzer type has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many mass spectrometers use two or more mass analyzers for tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the more common mass analyzers listed below, there are others designed for special situations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] of motion in the non-relativistic case, i.e. valid only at ion velocity much lower than the speed of light).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This differential equation is the classic equation of motion for charged particles.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Together with the particle's initial conditions, it completely determines the particle's motion in space and time in terms of *m/Q*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus mass spectrometers could be thought of as "mass-to-charge spectrometers".
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] When presenting data, it is common to use the (officially) dimensionless *m/z*, where z is the number of elementary charges (*e*) on the ion (z=Q/e).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This quantity, although it is informally called the mass-to-charge ratio, more accurately speaking represents the ratio of the mass number and the charge number, *z*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are several important analyzer characteristics.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass resolving power** $\Delta (m/z)$ is the just detectable difference in *m/z*, at that particular *m/z*, usually measured measured in milli mass units (mDa).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In particular, the resolution may be different at different *m/z*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is usually operationalized as the full width at half maximum a peak at that given *m/z*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A "high-resolution" mass analyzer typically has resolution >1 million.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, that means it can resolve two peaks at ~1 kDa, differing by just ~1 mDa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **absolute accuracy** is the ratio of the *m/z* measurement error to the true *m/z*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass range** is the range of *m/z* that a given analyzer can analyze.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **speed** is the number of spectra lines per unit time that can be generated.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, higher resolution requires lower speed, and vice versa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some mass spectrometers, such as the Fourier transform spectrometers, allow a continuous tradeoff between speed and resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A sector-type mass analyzer uses a static electric and/or magnetic field to control the path of the ion beam.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common type uses a magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a simplified case, the field is a constant field B , and we have an ion of mass m and charge $ze$ that enters the field perpendicularly at velocity v .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Then, in the field, the ion undergoes circular motion of radius $R={\tfrac {v(m/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer has accelerated the ion under a known voltage V , then the kinetic energy of the ion is $KE=zeV={\tfrac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ , giving $m/z={\frac {eR^{2}B^{2}}{2V}}$ Thus, the single input ion beam is analyzed into a fan of ion beams, the higher m/z ions turning at a larger radius.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can then select for one m/z by using a moving narrow slit.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can also use a fixed narrow slit, but vary V or B .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If there is just a single detector, then the analyzer can sweep across the mass spectrum one slit at a time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] With multiple detectors, the speed of analysis increases.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A pure magnetic sector analyzer can achieve resolution ~10,000.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] With an added electrostatic focusing field before or after the magnetic sector, the analyzer can achieve resolution ~100,000.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Particularly unstable ions may disintegrate while passing through the analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If it undergoes the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts) when entering the analyzer, it would undergo a circular motion of radius $R'={\tfrac {v(m'/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This would then show up in the resulting spectrogram as a peak that is *apparently* made by an ion with $(m^{*}/z)=({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since there is no actual ion with mass $m^{*}$ , this is called an abnormal peak, or a **metastable ion peak**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In general, a meta stable ion peak is a broad peak centered at a highly non-integer value of $m^{*}/z$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The existence of a metastable ion peak at $({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ is strong evidence that two ions of masses $m/z,m'/z$ are in fact related by the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The time-of-flight (TOF) analyzer takes as input a short *pulse* of ions, and lets it fly through a long vacuum tube.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions with different m/z would arrive at the end of the tube at different times, thus analyzing them.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions must enter the tube as pulses, because otherwise the TOF cannot be measured.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer outputs a continuous stream of ions, then it must be cut up into ion pulses, by methods such as a fast mechanical shutter, an oscillating electric field plus a narrow slit, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The MALDI ionizer is particularly well-suited for TOF analyzer, since the laser used in MALDI is usually a high-intensity pulse laser.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDI-TOF has allowed measurement of mass spetrograms using only a few attomoles of material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, let the length of the analyzer be L , then the time taken for an ion of velocity v to pass through the analyzer is $t=L/v$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In that case, we have $m/z=(m/z)_{0}+{\frac {4eVt_{0}}{L^{2}}}\delta t$ This means that the signal can be measured by an oscilloscope in trigger mode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, the first GC-MS was done in 1950 using an oscilloscope.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The experimenters took quick photos of the oscilloscope screen for each component exiting the gas chromatography machine.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This distribution in velocities broadens the peaks shown on the count vs *m/z* plot, but will generally not change the central location of the peaks, since the starting velocity of ions is generally centered at zero.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] To fix this problem, time-lag focusing/delayed extraction has been coupled with TOF-MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ions do not start at identical kinetic energies, then some ions may lag behind higher kinetic energy ions decreasing resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Reflectron geometries are commonly employed to correct this problem.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Longer tubes result in higher resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector doubles the effective tube length.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector-TOF can reach a resolution of several thousands.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For their low resolution, TOF mass spectrometers makes up for it in speed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are particularly useful in chemical kinetics studies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can study rapid reactions such as combustion and explosions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A quadrupole mass analyzers uses four parallel metal rods to create a quadrupole electrical field oscillating at radio frequency (RF), to selectively stabilize or destabilize the paths of ions passing through.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] With each oscillation pattern, the ions passing through would undergo a helical motion.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ion has *m/z* within a certain range, the helical motion is stable.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Otherwise, the helical motion will increase in amplitude until the ion collides with the rods.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This means that only ions with m/z within a narrow range can go through it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The full spectrogram can be swept through by changing the potentials on the rods, continuously or in a succession of discrete hops.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are typically of low resolution ~1000, but they are cheap and small, so are good for "desktop" mass spectrometers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole mass filter is closely related to the quadrupole ion trap, particularly the linear quadrupole ion trap except that it is designed to pass the untrapped ions rather than collect the trapped ones, and is for that reason referred to as a **transmission quadrupole**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap itself can be used as an analyzer, as in ion trap analyzers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A common variation of the transmission quadrupole is the triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The "triple quad" has three consecutive quadrupole stages, the first acting as a mass filter to transmit a particular incoming ion to the second quadrupole, a collision chamber, wherein that ion can be broken into fragments.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The third quadrupole also acts as a mass filter, to transmit a particular fragment ion to the detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a kind of MS/MS, and so it can perform various scan types characteristic of MS/MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A magnetically enhanced quadrupole mass analyzer has an additional magnetic field, axial or transverse.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap works on the same physical principles as the quadrupole mass analyzer, but the ions are trapped and sequentially ejected.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are trapped in a mainly quadrupole RF field, in a space defined by a ring electrode (usually connected to the main RF potential) between two endcap electrodes (typically connected to DC or auxiliary AC potentials).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is ionized either internally (e.g. with an electron or laser beam), or externally, in which case the ions are often introduced through an aperture in an endcap electrode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many mass/charge separation and isolation methods but the most commonly used is the mass instability mode in which the RF potential is ramped so that the orbit of ions with a mass *a* > *b* are stable while ions with mass *b* become unstable and are ejected on the *z*-axis onto a detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are also non-destructive analysis methods.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The cylindrical ion trap mass spectrometer (CIT) is a derivative of the quadrupole ion trap where the electrodes are formed from flat rings rather than hyperbolic shaped electrodes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The architecture lends itself well to miniaturization because as the size of a trap is reduced, the shape of the electric field near the center of the trap, the region where the ions are trapped, forms a shape similar to that of a hyperbolic trap.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A linear quadrupole ion trap is similar to a quadrupole ion trap, but it traps ions in a two dimensional quadrupole field, instead of a three-dimensional quadrupole field as in a 3D quadrupole ion trap.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thermo Fisher's LTQ ("linear trap quadrupole") is an example of the linear ion trap.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A toroidal ion trap can be visualized as a linear quadrupole curved around and connected at the ends or as a cross-section of a 3D ion trap rotated on edge to form the toroid, donut-shaped trap.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The trap can store large volumes of ions by distributing them throughout the ring-like trap structure.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This toroidal shaped trap is a configuration that allows the increased miniaturization of an ion trap mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Additionally, all ions are stored in the same trapping field and ejected together simplifying detection that can be complicated with array configurations due to variations in detector alignment and machining of the arrays.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] As with the toroidal trap, linear traps and 3D quadrupole ion traps are the most commonly miniaturized mass analyzers due to their high sensitivity, tolerance for mTorr pressure, and capabilities for single analyzer tandem mass spectrometry (e.g. product ion scans).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Fourier-transform mass spectrometry (FTMS), or more precisely Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (FT-ICR MS), measures mass by detecting the image current produced by ions spiralling in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Instead of measuring the deflection of ions with a detector such as an electron multiplier, the ions are injected into a Penning trap (a static electric/magnetic ion trap) where they effectively form part of a circuit.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Detectors at fixed positions in space measure the electrical signal of ions which pass near them over time, producing a periodic signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since the frequency of an ion's cycling is determined by its *m/z* ratio, this can be deconvoluted by Fourier transform on the signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ion cyclotron resonance (ICR) is an older mass analysis technique.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is similar to FTMS, in that the ions undergo cyclotron resonane.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, the ions are detected with a traditional detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions trapped in a Penning trap are excited by an RF electric field until they impact the wall of the trap, where the detector is located.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions of different mass are resolved according to impact time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] FTMS is generally the most sensitive analyzer on the market, achieving resolution ~1 million.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It achieves such high resolution, since each ion is "counted" multiple times by the spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] From the perspective of the uncertainty principle of signal processing, an oscillating signal that is highly *delocalized* in time is also highly *localized* in frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitrap analyzers are similar to FTMS analyzers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are electrostatically trapped in an orbit around a central, spindle shaped electrode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrode confines the ions so that they both orbit around the central electrode and oscillate back and forth along the central electrode's long axis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This oscillation generates an image current in the detector plates which is recorded by the instrument.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The frequencies of these image currents depend on the mass-to-charge ratios of the ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectra are obtained by Fourier transformation of the recorded image currents.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitraps have a high mass accuracy, high sensitivity and a good dynamic range.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some chemical species have the same chemical composition, but different isotopes (isotopomers).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can be distinguished by a very basic analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, isotopes were discovered in 1922, very early in the history of mass spectrometry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, two chemical species can have the same number of nucleons (neutrons and protons).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C3 and SH4 both have 36 nucleons.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can still be distinguished, since proton and neutron mass differ by 1.4 mDa, and since different nuclei have different binding energy, which by $E=mc^{2}$ results in a different mass.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The net result is that C3 and S1H4 differ by 3.4 mDa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Even smaller differences are achievable by carefully matching isotopes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C4 and S1H313C1 differ by 1.1 mDa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such differences can be resolved by high resolution mass spectrometry, which reaches resolution >1 million, sufficient to resolve ~1 mDa difference at *m/z* ~ 1000.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques for high resolution MS, but the highest resolution is achieved by FTMS with high magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] With increasing magnetic field strength, the resolution and spectral acquisition speed increases linearly, while mass accuracy and dynamic range increases quadratically.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the highest resolution is achieved by high field FTMS, up to 21 Tesla.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It reaches resolution >2.7 million at m/z ~ 400, and mass measurement accuracy < 80 ppb.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are often employed in geochemical and petrochemical studies, since there is a lot of money in petroleum industry, and petroleum composition is highly complex.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another application is in isotopic analysis of large proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two proteins differing by a single isotopic atom are separated by $\Delta m\approx 1$ , requiring a resolution of $m/\Delta m$ to resolve.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For large proteins with m > 100 kDa and z ~ 50, such as monoclonal antibodies, this requires an analyzer that achieves resolving power > 100,000 at m/z ~ 2000.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] High resolution FTMS is also very sensitive as a detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] It has allowed detecting proteins in the 8–20 kDa range at a sample concentration of ~30 zeptomole (i.e. about 20,000 *individual* molecules).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] When the mass of a single ion species is to be measured, the highest precision achievable is via Penning-type traps.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The PENTATRAP for example measures the mass of long-lived, highly charged, heavy ions, to a precision of $m/\Delta m>10^{11}$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is sufficiently sensitive to directly measure the energy of metastable electronic states to an accuracy of ~1 eV via the mass-energy equation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The final element of the mass spectrometer is the detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector records either the charge induced or the current produced when an ion passes by or hits a surface.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a scanning instrument, the signal produced in the detector during the course of the scan versus where the instrument is in the scan (at what *m/Q*) will produce a mass spectrum, a record of ions as a function of *m/Q*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **linear dynamic range** is the range over which the detector signal is linear with analyte concentration.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, some type of electron multiplier is used, though other detectors including Faraday cups and ion-to-photon detectors are also used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Because the number of ions leaving the mass analyzer at a particular instant is typically quite small, considerable amplification is often necessary to get a signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Microchannel plate detectors are commonly used in modern commercial instruments.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In FTMS and Orbitraps, the detector consists of a pair of metal surfaces within the mass analyzer/ion trap region which the ions only pass near as they oscillate.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] No direct current is produced, only a weak AC image current is produced in a circuit between the electrodes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other inductive detectors have also been used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A tandem mass spectrometer is one capable of multiple rounds of mass spectrometry, usually separated by some form of molecule fragmentation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, one mass analyzer can isolate one peptide from many entering a mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A collision cell then stabilizes the peptide ions while they collide with a gas, causing them to fragment by collision-induced dissociation (CID).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] A further mass analyzer then sorts the fragments produced from the peptides.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem MS can also be done in a single mass analyzer over time, as in a quadrupole ion trap.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] An important application using tandem mass spectrometry is in protein identification.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem mass spectrometry enables a variety of experimental sequences.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many commercial mass spectrometers are designed to expedite the execution of such routine sequences as selected reaction monitoring, precursor ion scanning, product ion scanning, and neutral loss scanning.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another type of tandem mass spectrometry used for radiocarbon dating is accelerator mass spectrometry, which uses very high voltages, usually in the mega-volt range, to accelerate negative ions into a type of tandem mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **METLIN Metabolite and Chemical Entity Database** is the largest repository of experimental tandem mass spectrometry data acquired from standards.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] The tandem mass spectrometry data on over 960,000 molecular standards (as of October 2025) is provided to facilitate the identification of chemical entities from tandem mass spectrometry experiments.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the identification of known molecules it is also useful for identifying unknowns using its similarity searching/analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] All tandem mass spectrometry data comes from the experimental analysis of standards at multiple collision energies and in both positive and negative ionization modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] When a specific combination of source, analyzer, and detector becomes conventional in practice, a compound acronym may arise to designate it succinctly.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] One example is MALDI-TOF, which refers to a combination of a matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization source with a time-of-flight mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other examples include inductively coupled plasma-mass spectrometry (ICP-MS), accelerator mass spectrometry, thermal ionization-mass spectrometry (TIMS) and spark source mass spectrometry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] Certain applications of mass spectrometry have developed monikers that although strictly speaking would seem to refer to a broad application, in practice have come instead to connote a specific or a limited number of instrument configurations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p01] An example of this is isotope-ratio mass spectrometry, which refers in practice to the use of a limited number of sector based mass analyzers; this name is used to refer to both the application and the instrument used for the application.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important enhancement to the mass resolving and mass determining capabilities of mass spectrometry is using it in tandem with chromatographic and other separation techniques.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A common combination is gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC/MS or GC-MS).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this technique, a gas chromatograph is used to separate different compounds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This stream of separated compounds is fed online into the ion source, a metallic filament to which voltage is applied.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This filament emits electrons which ionize the compounds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The ions can then further fragment, yielding predictable patterns.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Intact ions and fragments pass into the mass spectrometer's analyzer and are eventually detected.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, the high temperatures (300 °C) used in the GC-MS injection port (and oven) can result in thermal degradation of injected molecules, thus resulting in the measurement of degradation products instead of the actual molecule(s) of interest.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Similarly to gas chromatography MS (GC-MS), liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC/MS or LC-MS) separates compounds chromatographically before they are introduced to the ion source and mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] It differs from GC-MS in that the mobile phase is liquid, usually a mixture of water and organic solvents, instead of gas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most commonly, an electrospray ionization source is used in LC-MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other popular and commercially available LC-MS ion sources are atmospheric pressure chemical ionization and atmospheric pressure photoionization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] There are also some newly developed ionization techniques like laser spray.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Capillary electrophoresis–mass spectrometry (CE-MS) is a technique that combines the liquid separation process of capillary electrophoresis with mass spectrometry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] CE-MS is typically coupled to electrospray ionization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion mobility spectrometry-mass spectrometry (IMS/MS or IMMS) is a technique where ions are first separated by drift time through some neutral gas under an applied electrical potential gradient before being introduced into a mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Drift time is a measure of the collisional cross section relative to the charge of the ion.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS (the time over which the experiment takes place) is longer than most mass spectrometric techniques, such that the mass spectrometer can sample along the course of the IMS separation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This produces data about the IMS separation and the mass-to-charge ratio of the ions in a manner similar to LC-MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS is short relative to liquid chromatography or gas chromatography separations and can thus be coupled to such techniques, producing triple modalities such as LC/IMS/MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry produces various types of data.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common data representation is the mass spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Certain types of mass spectrometry data are best represented as a mass chromatogram.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Types of chromatograms include selected ion monitoring (SIM), total ion current (TIC), and selected reaction monitoring, among many others.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other types of mass spectrometry data are well represented as a three-dimensional contour map.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this form, the mass-to-charge, *m/z* is on the *x*-axis, intensity the *y*-axis, and an additional experimental parameter, such as time, is recorded on the *z*-axis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry data analysis is specific to the type of experiment producing the data.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] General subdivisions of data are fundamental to understanding any data.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Many mass spectrometers work in either *negative ion mode* or *positive ion mode*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is very important to know whether the observed ions are negatively or positively charged.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is often important in determining the neutral mass but it also indicates something about the nature of the molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Different types of ion source result in different arrays of fragments produced from the original molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] An electron ionization source produces many fragments and mostly single-charged (1-) radicals (odd number of electrons), whereas an electrospray source usually produces non-radical quasimolecular ions that are frequently multiply charged.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry purposely produces fragment ions post-source and can drastically change the sort of data achieved by an experiment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Knowledge of the origin of a sample can provide insight into the component molecules of the sample and their fragmentations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A sample from a synthesis/manufacturing process will probably contain impurities chemically related to the target component.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A crudely prepared biological sample will probably contain a certain amount of salt, which may form adducts with the analyte molecules in certain analyses.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Results can also depend heavily on sample preparation and how it was run/introduced.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important example is the issue of which matrix is used for MALDI spotting, since much of the energetics of the desorption/ionization event is controlled by the matrix rather than the laser power.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Sometimes samples are spiked with sodium or another ion-carrying species to produce adducts rather than a protonated species.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry can measure molar mass, molecular structure, and sample purity.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Each of these questions requires a different experimental procedure; therefore, adequate definition of the experimental goal is a prerequisite for collecting the proper data and successfully interpreting it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Since the precise structure or peptide sequence of a molecule is deciphered through the set of fragment masses, the interpretation of mass spectra requires combined use of various techniques.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Usually the first strategy for identifying an unknown compound is to compare its experimental mass spectrum against a library of mass spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] If no matches result from the search, then manual interpretation or software assisted interpretation of mass spectra must be performed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Computer simulation of ionization and fragmentation processes occurring in mass spectrometer is the primary tool for assigning structure or peptide sequence to a molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] An *a priori* structural information is fragmented *in silico* and the resulting pattern is compared with observed spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Such simulation is often supported by a fragmentation library that contains published patterns of known decomposition reactions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Software taking advantage of this idea has been developed for both small molecules and proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Analysis of mass spectra can also be spectra with accurate mass.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A mass-to-charge ratio value (*m/z*) with only integer precision can represent an immense number of theoretically possible ion structures; however, more precise mass figures significantly reduce the number of candidate molecular formulas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer algorithm called formula generator calculates all molecular formulas that theoretically fit a given mass with specified tolerance.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry has both qualitative and quantitative uses.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] These include identifying unknown compounds, determining the isotopic composition of elements in a molecule, and determining the structure of a compound by observing its fragmentation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other uses include quantifying the amount of a compound in a sample or studying the fundamentals of gas phase ion chemistry (the chemistry of ions and neutrals in a vacuum).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] MS is now commonly used in analytical laboratories that study physical, chemical, or biological properties of a great variety of compounds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Quantification can be relative (analyzed relative to a reference sample) or absolute (analyzed using a standard curve method).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A few of the disadvantages of the method is that it often fails to distinguish between optical and geometrical isomers and the positions of substituent in o-, m- and p- positions in an aromatic ring.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also, its scope is limited in identifying hydrocarbons that produce similar fragmented ions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is also used to determine the isotopic composition of elements within a sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Differences in mass among isotopes of an element are very small, and the less abundant isotopes of an element are typically very rare, so a very sensitive instrument is required.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] For the measurement of light elements (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] H,C,N,O,S), isotope ratio mass spectrometers usually use a single magnet to bend a beam of ionized particles towards a series of Faraday cups which convert particle impacts to electric current.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A fast on-line analysis of deuterium content of water can be done using flowing afterglow mass spectrometry, FA-MS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Probably the most sensitive and accurate mass spectrometer for this purpose is the accelerator mass spectrometry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is because it provides ultimate sensitivity, capable of measuring individual atoms and measuring nuclides with a dynamic range of ~1015 relative to the major stable isotope.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Isotopic signatures can serve as markers of a variety of processes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some isotope ratios are used to determine the age of materials for example as in carbon dating.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Labeling with stable isotopes is also used for protein quantification (see protein characterization below).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Membrane-introduction mass spectrometry combines the isotope ratio mass spectrometry with a reaction chamber/cell separated by a gas-permeable membrane.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method allows the study of gases as they evolve in solution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method has been extensively used for the study of the production of oxygen by Photosystem II.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Another technique with applications in trace gas analysis field is secondary electrospray ionization (SESI-MS), which is a variant of electrospray ionization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] SESI consist of an electrospray plume of pure acidified solvent that interacts with neutral vapors.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Vapor molecules get ionized at atmospheric pressure when charge is transferred from the ions formed in the electrospray to the molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] One advantage of this approach is that it is compatible with most ESI-MS systems.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A residual gas analyzer (RGA) is a small and usually rugged mass spectrometer, typically designed for process control and contamination monitoring in vacuum systems.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] When constructed as a quadrupole mass analyzer, there exist two implementations, utilizing either an open ion source (OIS) or a closed ion source (CIS).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs may be found in high vacuum applications such as research chambers, surface science setups, accelerators, scanning microscopes, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs are used in most cases to monitor the quality of the vacuum and easily detect minute traces of impurities in the low-pressure gas environment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] These impurities can be measured down to $10^{-14}$ Torr levels, possessing sub-ppm detectability in the absence of background interferences.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs would also be used as sensitive in-situ leak detectors commonly using helium, isopropyl alcohol or other tracer molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] With vacuum systems pumped down to lower than $10^{-5}$ Torr—checking of the integrity of the vacuum seals and the quality of the vacuum—air leaks, virtual leaks and other contaminants at low levels may be detected before a process is initiated.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] An atom probe is an instrument that combines time-of-flight mass spectrometry and field-evaporation microscopy to map the location of individual atoms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Pharmacokinetics is often studied using mass spectrometry because of the complex nature of the matrix (often blood or urine) and the need for high sensitivity to observe low dose and long time point data.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common instrumentation used in this application is LC-MS with a triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry is usually employed for added specificity.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Standard curves and internal standards are used for quantitation of usually a single pharmaceutical in the samples.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The samples represent different time points as a pharmaceutical is administered and then metabolized or cleared from the body.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Blank or t=0 samples taken before administration are important in determining background and ensuring data integrity with such complex sample matrices.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Much attention is paid to the linearity of the standard curve; however it is not uncommon to use curve fitting with more complex functions such as quadratics since the response of most mass spectrometers is less than linear across large concentration ranges.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] There is currently considerable interest in the use of very high sensitivity mass spectrometry for microdosing studies, which are seen as a promising alternative to animal experimentation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Recent studies show that secondary electrospray ionization (SESI) is a powerful technique to monitor drug kinetics via breath analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Because breath is naturally produced, several datapoints can be readily collected.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This allows for the number of collected data-points to be greatly increased.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In animal studies, this approach SESI can reduce animal sacrifice.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In humans, SESI-MS non-invasive analysis of breath can help study the kinetics of drugs at a personalized level.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is an important method for the characterization and sequencing of proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The two primary methods for ionization of whole proteins are electrospray ionization (ESI) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In keeping with the performance and mass range of available mass spectrometers, two approaches are used for characterizing proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the first, intact proteins are ionized by either of the two techniques described above, and then introduced to a mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This approach is referred to as "top-down" strategy of protein analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The top-down approach however is largely limited to low-throughput single-protein studies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the second, proteins are enzymatically digested into smaller peptides using proteases such as trypsin or pepsin, either in solution or in gel after electrophoretic separation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The collection of peptide products are often separated by chromatography prior to introduction to the mass analyzer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] When the characteristic pattern of peptides is used for the identification of the protein the method is called peptide mass fingerprinting (PMF), if the identification is performed using the sequence data determined in tandem MS analysis it is called de novo peptide sequencing.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] These procedures of protein analysis are also referred to as the "bottom-up" approach, and have also been used to analyse the distribution and position of post-translational modifications such as phosphorylation on proteins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A third approach is also beginning to be used, this intermediate "middle-down" approach involves analyzing proteolytic peptides that are larger than the typical tryptic peptide.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] As a standard method for analysis, mass spectrometers have reached other planets and moons.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Two were taken to Mars by the Viking program.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In early 2005 the Cassini–Huygens mission delivered a specialized GC-MS instrument aboard the Huygens probe through the atmosphere of Titan, the largest moon of the planet Saturn.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] This instrument analyzed atmospheric samples along its descent trajectory and was able to vaporize and analyze samples of Titan's frozen, hydrocarbon covered surface once the probe had landed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] These measurements compare the abundance of isotope(s) of each particle comparatively to earth's natural abundance.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also on board the Cassini–Huygens spacecraft was an ion and neutral mass spectrometer which had been taking measurements of Titan's atmospheric composition as well as the composition of Enceladus' plumes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A Thermal and Evolved Gas Analyzer mass spectrometer was carried by the Mars Phoenix Lander launched in 2007.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers are also widely used in space missions to measure the composition of plasmas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] For example, the Cassini spacecraft carried the Cassini Plasma Spectrometer (CAPS), which measured the mass of ions in Saturn's magnetosphere.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers were used in hospitals for respiratory gas analysis beginning around 1975 through the end of the century.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some are probably still in use but none are currently being manufactured.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Found mostly in the operating room, they were a part of a complex system, in which respired gas samples from patients undergoing anesthesia were drawn into the instrument through a valve mechanism designed to sequentially connect up to 32 rooms to the mass spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer directed all operations of the system.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The data collected from the mass spectrometer was delivered to the individual rooms for the anesthesiologist to use.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The uniqueness of this magnetic sector mass spectrometer may have been the fact that a plane of detectors, each purposely positioned to collect all of the ion species expected to be in the samples, allowed the instrument to simultaneously report all of the gases respired by the patient.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Although the mass range was limited to slightly over 120 u, fragmentation of some of the heavier molecules negated the need for a higher detection limit.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The primary function of mass spectrometry is as a tool for chemical analyses based on detection and quantification of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, mass spectrometry also shows promise for material synthesis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion soft landing is characterized by deposition of intact species on surfaces at low kinetic energies which precludes the fragmentation of the incident species.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] The soft landing technique was first reported in 1977 for the reaction of low energy sulfur containing ions on a lead surface.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most mass spectrometers measure the mass-to-charge ratio; the actual mass can be found only if the charge is known.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] For smaller molecules the charge can be determined from the spacing of isotope peaks, but for very large biomolecules and particles (in the megadalton range) resolution may not be adequate to separate isotope peaks, and thus the mass cannot be determined.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] In charge detection mass spectrometry (CDMS), the charge of an individual ion/particle is measured directly (alongside its mass-to-charge ratio) and therefore the true mass is known.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is a single-particle technique, but to produce more precise and accurate results, the data from many individually-measured ions can be combined.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The most commonly used nuclei are 1 H and 13 C, although isotopes of many other elements, such as 19 F, 31 P, and 29 Si, can be studied by high-field NMR spectroscopy as well.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In order to interact with the magnetic field in the spectrometer, the nucleus must have an intrinsic angular momentum and nuclear magnetic dipole moment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This occurs when an isotope has a nonzero nuclear spin, meaning an odd number of protons and/or neutrons (see Isotope).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Nuclides with even numbers of both have a total spin of zero and are therefore not NMR-active.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In its application to molecules the NMR effect can be observed only in the presence of a static magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] However, in the ordered phases of magnetic materials, very large internal fields are produced at the nuclei of magnetic ions (and of close ligands), which allow NMR to be performed in zero applied field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Additionally, radio-frequency transitions of nuclear spin I > ⁠1/2⁠ with large enough electric quadrupolar coupling to the electric field gradient at the nucleus may also be excited in zero applied magnetic field (nuclear quadrupole resonance).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In the dominant chemistry application, the use of higher fields improves the sensitivity of the method (signal-to-noise ratio scales approximately as the power of ⁠3/2⁠ with the magnetic field strength) and the spectral resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Commercial NMR spectrometers employing liquid helium cooled superconducting magnets with fields of up to 28 Tesla have been developed and are widely used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is a key feature of NMR that the resonance frequency of nuclei in a particular sample substance is usually directly proportional to the strength of the applied magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is this feature that is exploited in imaging techniques; if a sample is placed in a non-uniform magnetic field then the resonance frequencies of the sample's nuclei depend on where in the field they are located.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This effect serves as the basis of magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The two magnetic fields are usually chosen to be perpendicular to each other as this maximizes the NMR signal strength.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The frequencies of the time-signal response by the total magnetization (**M**) of the nuclear spins are analyzed in NMR spectroscopy and magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The information provided by NMR can also be increased using hyperpolarization, and/or using two-dimensional, three-dimensional and higher-dimensional techniques.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] NMR phenomena are also utilized in low-field NMR, NMR spectroscopy and MRI in the Earth's magnetic field (referred to as Earth's field NMR), and in several types of magnetometers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Nuclear magnetic resonance was first described and measured in molecular beams by Isidor Rabi in 1938, by extending the Stern–Gerlach experiment, and in 1944, Rabi was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for this work.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In 1946, Felix Bloch and Edward Mills Purcell expanded the technique for use on liquids and solids, for which they shared the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1952.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Varian filed the "Method and means for correlating nuclear properties of atoms and magnetic fields", U.S. patent 2,561,490 on October 21, 1948 and was accepted on July 24, 1951.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Varian Associates developed the first NMR unit called NMR HR-30 in 1952.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Purcell had worked on the development of radar during World War II at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Radiation Laboratory.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] His work during that project on the production and detection of radio frequency power and on the absorption of such RF power by matter laid the foundation for his discovery of NMR in bulk matter.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Rabi, Bloch, and Purcell observed that magnetic nuclei, like 1 H and 31 P, could absorb RF energy when placed in a magnetic field and when the RF was of a frequency specific to the identity of the nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] When this absorption occurs, the nucleus is described as being *in resonance*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Different atomic nuclei within a molecule resonate at different (radio) frequencies in the same applied static magnetic field, due to various local magnetic fields.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The observation of such magnetic resonance frequencies of the nuclei present in a molecule makes it possible to determine essential chemical and structural information about the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The improvements of the NMR method benefited from the development of electromagnetic technology and advanced electronics and their introduction into civilian use.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It soon showed its potential in organic chemistry, where NMR has become indispensable, and by the 1990s improvement in the sensitivity and resolution of NMR spectroscopy resulted in its broad use in analytical chemistry, biochemistry and materials science.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In the 2020s zero- to ultralow-field nuclear magnetic resonance (ZULF NMR), a form of spectroscopy that provides abundant analytical results without the need for large magnetic fields, was developed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is combined with a special technique that makes it possible to hyperpolarize atomic nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] All nucleons, that is neutrons and protons, composing any atomic nucleus, have the intrinsic quantum property of spin, an intrinsic angular momentum analogous to the classical angular momentum of a spinning sphere.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The overall spin of the nucleus is determined by the spin quantum number *S*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] If the numbers of both the protons and neutrons in a given nuclide are even then the system prefers to minimize its spin, giving *S* = 0, i.e. there is no overall spin.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Then, just as electrons pair up in nondegenerate atomic orbitals, so do even numbers of protons or even numbers of neutrons (both of which are also spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles and hence fermions), giving zero overall spin.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] However, an unpaired proton and unpaired neutron will have a lower energy when their spins are parallel, not anti-parallel.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This parallel spin alignment of distinguishable particles does not violate the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The lowering of energy for parallel spins has to do with the quark structure of these two nucleons.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] As a result, the spin ground state for the deuteron (the nucleus of deuterium, the 2H isotope of hydrogen), which has only a proton and a neutron, corresponds to a spin value of **1**, *not of zero*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] On the other hand, because of the Pauli exclusion principle, the tritium isotope of hydrogen must have a pair of anti-parallel spin neutrons (of total spin zero for the neutron spin-pair), plus a proton of spin ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Therefore, the tritium total nuclear spin value is again ⁠1/2⁠, just like the simpler, abundant hydrogen isotope, 1H nucleus (the *proton*).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The NMR absorption frequency for tritium is also similar to that of 1H.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In many other cases of *non-radioactive* nuclei, the overall spin is also non-zero and may have a contribution from the orbital angular momentum of the unpaired nucleon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] For example, the 27 Al nucleus has an overall spin value *S* = ⁠5/2⁠.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A non-zero spin ${\vec {S}}$ is associated with a non-zero magnetic dipole moment, ${\vec {\mu }}$ , via the relation ${\vec {\mu }}=\gamma {\vec {S}}$ where *γ* is the gyromagnetic ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Classically, this corresponds to the proportionality between the angular momentum and the magnetic dipole moment of a spinning charged sphere, both of which are vectors parallel to the rotation axis whose length increases proportional to the spinning frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is the magnetic moment and its interaction with magnetic fields that allows the observation of NMR signal associated with transitions between nuclear spin levels during resonant RF irradiation or caused by Larmor precession of the average magnetic moment after resonant irradiation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Nuclides with even numbers of both protons and neutrons have zero nuclear magnetic dipole moment and hence do not exhibit NMR signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] For instance, 18 O is an example of a nuclide that produces no NMR signal, whereas 13 C, 31 P, 35 Cl and 37 Cl are nuclides that do exhibit NMR spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The last two nuclei have spin *S* > ⁠1/2⁠ and are therefore quadrupolar nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Electron spin resonance (ESR) is a related technique in which transitions between electronic rather than nuclear spin levels are detected.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The basic principles are similar but the instrumentation, data analysis, and detailed theory are significantly different.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Moreover, there is a much smaller number of molecules and materials with unpaired electron spins that exhibit ESR (or electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR)) absorption than those that have NMR absorption spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] On the other hand, ESR has much higher signal per spin than NMR does.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Nuclear spin is an intrinsic angular momentum that is quantized.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This means that the magnitude of this angular momentum is quantized (i.e.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] *S* can only take on a restricted range of values), and also that the x, y, and z-components of the angular momentum are quantized, being restricted to integer or half-integer multiples of *ħ*, the reduced Planck constant.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The integer or half-integer quantum number associated with the spin component along the z-axis or the applied magnetic field is known as the magnetic quantum number, *m*, and can take values from +*S* to −*S*, in integer steps.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Hence for any given nucleus, there are a total of 2*S* + 1 angular momentum states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The *z*-component of the angular momentum vector ( ${\vec {S}}$ ) is therefore *Sz* = *mħ*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Consider nuclei with a spin of one-half, like 1 H, 13 C or 19 F.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Each nucleus has two linearly independent spin states, with *m* = ⁠1/2⁠ or *m* = −⁠1/2⁠ (also referred to as spin-up and spin-down, or sometimes α and β spin states, respectively) for the z-component of spin.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In the absence of a magnetic field, these states are degenerate; that is, they have the same energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Hence the number of nuclei in these two states will be essentially equal at thermal equilibrium.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] If a nucleus with spin is placed in a magnetic field, however, the two states no longer have the same energy as a result of the interaction between the nuclear magnetic dipole moment and the external magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] As a result, the different nuclear spin states have different energies in a non-zero magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In less formal language, we can talk about the two spin states of a spin ⁠1/2⁠ as being *aligned* either with or against the magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] If *γ* is positive (true for most isotopes used in NMR) then *m* = ⁠1/2⁠ ("spin up") is the lower energy state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The energy difference between the two states is: $\Delta {E}=\gamma \hbar B_{0}\,,$ and this results in a small population bias favoring the lower energy state in thermal equilibrium.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] With more spins pointing up than down, a net spin magnetization along the magnetic field **B**0 results.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A central concept in NMR is the precession of the spin magnetization around the magnetic field at the nucleus, with the angular frequency $\omega =-\gamma B$ where $\omega =2\pi \nu$ relates to the oscillation frequency $\nu$ and *B* is the magnitude of the field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This means that the spin magnetization, which is proportional to the sum of the spin vectors of nuclei in magnetically equivalent sites (the expectation value of the spin vector in quantum mechanics), moves on a cone around the **B** field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This is analogous to the precessional motion of the axis of a tilted spinning top around the gravitational field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In quantum mechanics, $\omega$ is the *Bohr frequency* $\Delta {E}/\hbar$ of the $S_{x}$ and $S_{y}$ expectation values.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Precession of non-equilibrium magnetization in the applied magnetic field **B**0 occurs with the Larmor frequency $\omega _{L}=2\pi \nu _{L}=-\gamma B_{0},$ without change in the populations of the energy levels because energy is constant (time-independent Hamiltonian).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A perturbation of nuclear spin orientations from equilibrium will occur only when an oscillating magnetic field is applied whose frequency *ν*rf sufficiently closely matches the Larmor precession frequency *ν*L of the nuclear magnetization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The populations of the spin-up and -down energy levels then undergo Rabi oscillations, which are analyzed most easily in terms of precession of the spin magnetization around the effective magnetic field in a reference frame rotating with the frequency *ν*rf.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The stronger the oscillating field, the faster the Rabi oscillations or the precession around the effective field in the rotating frame.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is the transverse magnetization generated by a resonant oscillating field which is usually detected in NMR, during application of the relatively weak RF field in old-fashioned continuous-wave NMR, or after the relatively strong RF pulse in modern pulsed NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It might appear from the above that all nuclei of the same nuclide (and hence the same *γ*) would resonate at exactly the same frequency but this is not the case.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The most important perturbation of the NMR frequency for applications of NMR is the "shielding" effect of the shells of electrons surrounding the nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Electrons, similar to the nucleus, are also charged and rotate with a spin to produce a magnetic field opposite to the applied magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In general, this electronic shielding reduces the magnetic field *at the nucleus* (which is what determines the NMR frequency).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] As a result, the frequency required to achieve resonance is also reduced.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Unless the local symmetry of such molecular orbitals is very high (leading to "isotropic" shift), the shielding effect will depend on the orientation of the molecule with respect to the external field (**B**0).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In solid-state NMR spectroscopy, magic angle spinning is required to average out this orientation dependence in order to obtain frequency values at the average or isotropic chemical shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This is unnecessary in conventional NMR investigations of molecules in solution, since rapid "molecular tumbling" averages out the chemical shift anisotropy (CSA).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In this case, the "average" chemical shift (ACS) or isotropic chemical shift is often simply referred to as the chemical shift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In 1949, Suryan first suggested that the interaction between a radiofrequency coil and a sample's bulk magnetization could explain why experimental observations of relaxation times differed from theoretical predictions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] RD occurs when transverse bulk magnetization from the sample, following a radio frequency pulse, induces an electromagnetic field (emf) in the receiver coil of the NMR spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This generates an oscillating current and a non-linear induced transverse magnetic field which returns the spin system to equilibrium faster than other mechanisms of relaxation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] RD can result in line broadening and measurement of a shorter spin-lattice relaxation time ( $T_{1}$ ).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] For instance, a sample of water in a 400 MHz NMR spectrometer will have $T_{RD}$ around 20 ms, whereas its $T_{1}$ is hundreds of milliseconds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This effect is often described using modified Bloch equations that include terms for radiation damping alongside the conventional relaxation terms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The longitudinal relaxation time of radiation damping ( $T_{RD}$ ) is given by the equation [1].
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The quantification of line broadening due to radiation damping can be determined by measuring the $\Delta v_{\frac {1}{2}}$ and use equation [2].
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Radiation damping in NMR is influenced significantly by system parameters.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It is notably more prominent in systems where the NMR probe possesses a high quality factor ( Q ) and a high filling factor, resulting in a strong coupling between the probe coil and the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The phenomenon is also impacted by the concentration of the nuclei within the sample and their magnetic moments, which can intensify the effects of radiation damping.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The strength of the magnetic field is inversely proportional to the lifetime of RD.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The impact of radiation damping on NMR signals is multifaceted.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] It can accelerate the decay of the NMR signal faster than intrinsic relaxation processes would suggest.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This acceleration can complicate the interpretation of NMR spectra by causing broadening of spectral lines, distorting multiplet structures, and introducing artifacts, especially in high-resolution NMR scenarios.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Such effects make it challenging to obtain clear and accurate data without considering the influence of radiation damping.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] To mitigate these effects, various strategies are employed in NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] These methods majorly stem from hardware or software.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Hardware modifications including RF feed-circuit and Q-factor switches reduce the feedback loop between the sample magnetization and the electromagnetic field induced by the coil and function successfully.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Other approaches such as designing selective pulse sequences also effectively manage the fields induced by radiation damping.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] These approaches aim to control and limit the disruptive effects of radiation damping during NMR experiments and all approaches are successful in eliminating RD to a fairly large extent.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Overall, understanding and managing radiation damping is crucial for obtaining high-quality NMR data, especially in modern high-field spectrometers where the effects can be significant due to the increased sensitivity and resolution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The process of population relaxation refers to nuclear spins that return to thermodynamic equilibrium in the magnet.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This process is also called *T*1, "spin-lattice" or "longitudinal magnetic" relaxation, where *T*1 refers to the mean time for an individual nucleus to return to its thermal equilibrium state of the spins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] After the nuclear spin population has relaxed, it can be probed again, since it is in the initial, equilibrium (mixed) state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The precessing nuclei can also fall out of alignment with each other and gradually stop producing a signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This is called *T*2, "spin-spin" or *transverse relaxation*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In practice, the value of *T*2*, which is the actually observed decay time of the observed NMR signal, or free induction decay (to ⁠1/*e*⁠ of the initial amplitude immediately after the resonant RF pulse), also depends on the static magnetic field inhomogeneity, which may be quite significant.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] (There is also a smaller but significant contribution to the observed FID shortening from the RF inhomogeneity of the resonant pulse).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In the corresponding FT-NMR spectrum—meaning the Fourier transform of the free induction decay— the width of the NMR signal in frequency units is inversely related to the *T*2* time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Thus, a nucleus with a long *T*2* relaxation time gives rise to a very sharp NMR peak in the FT-NMR spectrum for a very homogeneous ("well-shimmed") static magnetic field, whereas nuclei with shorter *T*2* values give rise to broad FT-NMR peaks even when the magnet is shimmed well.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Both *T*1 and *T*2 depend on the rate of molecular motions as well as the gyromagnetic ratios of both the resonating and their strongly interacting, next-neighbor nuclei that are not at resonance.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A Hahn echo decay experiment can be used to measure the dephasing time, as shown in the animation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The size of the echo is recorded for different spacings of the two pulses.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This reveals the decoherence that is not refocused by the 180° pulse.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In simple cases, an exponential decay is measured which is described by the *T*2 time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] NMR spectroscopy is one of the principal techniques used to obtain physical, chemical, electronic and structural information about molecules due to the chemical shift of the resonance frequencies of the nuclear spins in the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Peak splittings due to J- or dipolar couplings between nuclei are also useful.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] NMR spectroscopy can provide detailed and quantitative information on the functional groups, topology, dynamics and three-dimensional structure of molecules in solution and the solid state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Since the area under an NMR peak is usually proportional to the number of spins involved, peak integrals can be used to determine composition quantitatively.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A common methodology involves an extended delay time between each spectral scan (generally, 5 times the longest *T*1 in a complex mixture for a 90 degree pulsing angle, where *T*1 can be calculated using techniques such as FLIPS).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This lets nuclei relax completely, allowing integrals to be more accurate for quantitation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Additional structural and chemical information may be obtained by performing double-quantum NMR experiments for pairs of spins or quadrupolar nuclei such as 2 H.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Furthermore, nuclear magnetic resonance is one of the techniques that has been used to design quantum automata, and also build elementary quantum computers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] When the oscillation frequency matches the nuclear resonance frequency, the transverse magnetization is maximized and a peak is observed in the spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This is the origin of the counterintuitive, but still common, "high field" and "low field" terminology for low frequency and high frequency regions, respectively, of the NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] As of 1996, CW instruments were still used for routine work because the older instruments were cheaper to maintain and operate, often operating at 60 MHz with correspondingly weaker (non-superconducting) electromagnets cooled with water rather than liquid helium.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] One radio coil operated continuously, sweeping through a range of frequencies, while another orthogonal coil, designed not to receive radiation from the transmitter, received signals from nuclei that reoriented in solution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] As of 2014, low-end refurbished 60 MHz and 90 MHz systems were sold as FT-NMR instruments, and in 2010 the "average workhorse" NMR instrument was configured for 300 MHz.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] CW spectroscopy is inefficient in comparison with Fourier analysis techniques (see below) since it probes the NMR response at individual frequencies or field strengths in succession.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Since the NMR signal is intrinsically weak, the observed spectrum suffers from a poor signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This can be mitigated by signal averaging, i.e. adding the spectra from repeated measurements.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] While the NMR signal is the same in each scan and so adds linearly, the random noise adds more slowly – proportional to the square root of the number of spectra added (see random walk).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Hence the overall signal-to-noise ratio increases as the square-root of the number of spectra measured.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] However, monitoring an NMR signal at a single frequency as a function of time may be better suited for kinetic studies than pulsed Fourier-transform NMR spectrosocopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Most applications of NMR involve full NMR spectra, that is, the intensity of the NMR signal as a function of frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Early attempts to acquire the NMR spectrum more efficiently than simple CW methods involved illuminating the target simultaneously with more than one frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] A revolution in NMR occurred when short radio-frequency pulses began to be used, with a frequency centered at the middle of the NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The restricted range of the NMR frequencies for most light spin-⁠1/2⁠ nuclei made it relatively easy to use short (1 - 100 microsecond) radio frequency pulses to excite the entire NMR spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Applying such a pulse to a set of nuclear spins simultaneously excites all the single-quantum NMR transitions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In terms of the net magnetization vector, this corresponds to tilting the magnetization vector away from its equilibrium position (aligned along the external magnetic field).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The out-of-equilibrium magnetization vector then precesses about the external magnetic field vector at the NMR frequency of the spins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This oscillating magnetization vector induces a voltage in a nearby pickup coil, creating an electrical signal oscillating at the NMR frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This signal is known as the free induction decay (FID), and it contains the sum of the NMR responses from all the excited spins.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In order to obtain the frequency-domain NMR spectrum (NMR absorption intensity vs.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] NMR frequency) this time-domain signal (intensity vs. time) must be Fourier transformed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Fortunately, the development of Fourier transform (FT) NMR coincided with the development of digital computers and the digital fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Fourier methods can be applied to many types of spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Ernst was one of the pioneers of pulsed NMR and won a Nobel Prize in chemistry in 1991 for his work on Fourier Transform NMR and his development of multi-dimensional NMR spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The use of pulses of different durations, frequencies, or shapes in specifically designed patterns or *pulse sequences* allows production of a spectrum that contains many different types of information about the molecules in the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In multi-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, there are at least two pulses: one leads to the directly detected signal and the others affect the starting magnetization and spin state prior to it.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The full analysis involves repeating the sequence with the pulse timings systematically varied in order to probe the oscillations of the spin system are point by point in the time domain.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Multidimensional Fourier transformation of the multidimensional time signal yields the multidimensional spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In two-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (2D-NMR), there will be one systematically varied time period in the sequence of pulses, which will modulate the intensity or phase of the detected signals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In 3D-NMR, two time periods will be varied independently, and in 4D-NMR, three will be varied.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In some, fixed time intervals allow (among other things) magnetization transfer between nuclei and, therefore, the detection of the kinds of nuclear–nuclear interactions that allowed for the magnetization transfer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Interactions that can be detected are usually classified into two kinds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] There are *through-bond* and *through-space* interactions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Through-bond interactions relate to structural connectivity of the atoms and provide information about which ones are directly connected to each other, connected by way of a single other intermediate atom, etc.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Through-space interactions relate to actual geometric distances and angles, including effects of dipolar coupling and the nuclear Overhauser effect.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Multi-dimensional FT NMR experiments were then further developed into powerful methodologies for studying molecules in solution, in particular for the determination of the structure of biopolymers such as proteins or even small nucleic acids.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In 2002 Kurt Wüthrich shared the Nobel Prize in Chemistry (with John Bennett Fenn and Koichi Tanaka) for his work with protein FT NMR in solution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] This technique complements X-ray crystallography in that it is frequently applicable to molecules in an amorphous or liquid-crystalline state, whereas crystallography, as the name implies, is performed on molecules in a crystalline phase.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In electronically conductive materials, the Knight shift of the resonance frequency can provide information on the mobile charge carriers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Though nuclear magnetic resonance is used to study the structure of solids, extensive atomic-level structural detail is more challenging to obtain in the solid state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Due to broadening by chemical shift anisotropy (CSA) and dipolar couplings to other nuclear spins, without special techniques such as MAS or dipolar decoupling by RF pulses, the observed spectrum is often only a broad Gaussian band for non-quadrupolar spins in a solid.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Professor Raymond Andrew at the University of Nottingham in the UK pioneered the development of high-resolution solid-state nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] He was the first to report the introduction of the MAS (magic angle sample spinning; MASS) technique that allowed him to achieve spectral resolution in solids sufficient to distinguish between chemical groups with either different chemical shifts or distinct Knight shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Correct alignment of the sample rotation axis as close as possible to *θ*m is essential for cancelling out the chemical-shift anisotropy broadening.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] There are different angles for the sample spinning relative to the applied field for the averaging of electric quadrupole interactions and paramagnetic interactions, correspondingly ~30.6° and ~70.1°.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In amorphous materials, residual line broadening remains since each segment is in a slightly different environment, therefore exhibiting a slightly different NMR frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Line broadening or splitting by dipolar or J-couplings to nearby 1H nuclei is usually removed by radio-frequency pulses applied at the 1H frequency during signal detection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The concept of cross polarization developed by Sven Hartmann and Erwin Hahn was utilized in transferring magnetization from protons to less sensitive nuclei by M.G.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Significant further signal enhancement can be achieved by dynamic nuclear polarization from unpaired electrons to the nuclei, usually at temperatures near 110 K.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Because the intensity of nuclear magnetic resonance signals and, hence, the sensitivity of the technique depends on the strength of the magnetic field, the technique has also advanced over the decades with the development of more powerful magnets.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Advances made in audio-visual technology have also improved the signal-generation and processing capabilities of newer instruments.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] The most abundant naturally occurring isotopes of hydrogen and phosphorus (for example) are both magnetically susceptible and readily useful for nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] In contrast, carbon and nitrogen have useful isotopes but which occur only in very low natural abundance.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Other limitations on sensitivity arise from the quantum-mechanical nature of the phenomenon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] For quantum states separated by energy equivalent to radio frequencies, thermal energy from the environment causes the populations of the states to be close to equal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Since incoming radiation is equally likely to cause stimulated emission (a transition from the upper to the lower state) as absorption, the NMR effect depends on an excess of nuclei in the lower states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p01] Many isotopes of chemical elements can be used for NMR analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR is extensively used in medicine in the form of magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR is widely used in organic chemistry and industrially mainly for analysis of chemicals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The technique is also used to measure the ratio between water and fat in foods, monitor the flow of corrosive fluids in pipes, or to study molecular structures such as catalysts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The application of nuclear magnetic resonance best known to the general public is magnetic resonance imaging for medical diagnosis and magnetic resonance microscopy in research settings.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] However, it is also widely used in biochemical studies, notably in NMR spectroscopy such as proton NMR, carbon-13 NMR, deuterium NMR and phosphorus-31 NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Biochemical information can also be obtained from living tissue (e.g. human brain tumors) with the technique known as in vivo magnetic resonance spectroscopy or chemical shift NMR microscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] These spectroscopic studies are possible because nuclei are surrounded by orbiting electrons, which are charged particles that generate small, local magnetic fields that add to or subtract from the external magnetic field, and so will partially shield the nuclei.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The amount of shielding depends on the exact local environment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] For example, a hydrogen bonded to an oxygen will be shielded differently from a hydrogen bonded to a carbon atom.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] In addition, two hydrogen nuclei can interact via a process known as spin–spin coupling, if they are on the same molecule, which will split the lines of the spectra in a recognizable way.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] As one of the two major spectroscopic techniques used in metabolomics, NMR is used to generate metabolic fingerprints from biological fluids to obtain information about disease states or toxic insults.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The aforementioned chemical shift came as a disappointment to physicists who had hoped that the resonance frequency of each nuclear species would be constant in a given magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Dharmatti pioneered a way to determine the structure of many compounds by studying the peaks of nuclear magnetic resonance spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] It can be a very selective technique, distinguishing among many atoms within a molecule or collection of molecules of very similar type but which differ only in terms of their local chemical environment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR spectroscopy is used to unambiguously identify known and novel compounds, and as such, is usually required by scientific journals for identity confirmation of synthesized new compounds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] See the articles on carbon-13 NMR and proton NMR for detailed discussions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] A chemist can determine the identity of a compound by comparing the observed nuclear precession frequencies to known or predicted frequencies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Further structural data can be elucidated by observing *spin–spin coupling*, a process by which the precession frequency of a nucleus can be influenced by the spin orientation of a chemically bonded nucleus.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Spin–spin coupling is easily observed in NMR of hydrogen-1 (1 H NMR) since its natural abundance is nearly 100%.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] At low enough temperatures, a distinction can be made between the axial and equatorial hydrogens in cyclohexane.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] An example of nuclear magnetic resonance being used in the determination of a structure is that of buckminsterfullerene (often called "buckyballs", composition C60).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] This now famous form of carbon has 60 carbon atoms forming a sphere.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The carbon atoms are all in identical environments and so should see the same internal **H** field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Unfortunately, buckminsterfullerene contains no hydrogen and so 13 C nuclear magnetic resonance has to be used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] 13 C spectra require longer acquisition times since carbon-13 is not the common isotope of carbon (unlike hydrogen, where 1 H is the common isotope).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] However, in 1990 the spectrum was obtained by R.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Taylor and co-workers at the University of Sussex and was found to contain a single peak, confirming the unusual structure of buckminsterfullerene.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) is a powerful analytical tool for investigating the local structure and ion dynamics in battery materials.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR provides unique insights into the short-range atomic environments within complex electrochemical systems such as batteries.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Electrochemical processes rely on redox reactions, in which 7Li or 23Na are often involved.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Accordingly, their NMR spectroscopies are affected by the electronic structure of the material, which makes NMR an essential technique for probing the behavior of battery components during operation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] While NMR is primarily used for structural determination, it can also be used for purity determination, provided that the structure and molecular weight of the compound is known.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] This technique requires the use of an internal standard of known purity.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Typically this standard will have a high molecular weight to facilitate accurate weighing, but relatively few protons so as to give a clear peak for later integration e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Accurately weighed portions of the standard and sample are combined and analysed by NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Suitable peaks from both compounds are selected and the purity of the sample is determined via the following equation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Nuclear magnetic resonance is extremely useful for analyzing samples non-destructively.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Radio-frequency magnetic fields easily penetrate many types of matter and anything that is not highly conductive or inherently ferromagnetic.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] For example, various expensive biological samples, such as nucleic acids, including RNA and DNA, or proteins, can be studied using nuclear magnetic resonance for weeks or months before using destructive biochemical experiments.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] This also makes nuclear magnetic resonance a good choice for analyzing dangerous samples.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] In addition to providing static information on molecules by determining their 3D structures, one of the remarkable advantages of NMR over X-ray crystallography is that it can be used to obtain important dynamic information.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] This is due to the orientation dependence of the chemical-shift, dipole-coupling, or electric-quadrupole-coupling contributions to the instantaneous NMR frequency in an anisotropic molecular environment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Another use for nuclear magnetic resonance is data acquisition in the petroleum industry for petroleum and natural gas exploration and recovery.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Initial research in this domain began in the 1950s, however, the first commercial instruments were not released until the early 1990s.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] A borehole is drilled into rock and sedimentary strata into which nuclear magnetic resonance logging equipment is lowered.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Nuclear magnetic resonance analysis of these boreholes is used to measure rock porosity, estimate permeability from pore size distribution and identify pore fluids (water, oil and gas).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] These instruments are typically low field NMR spectrometers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR logging, a subcategory of electromagnetic logging, measures the induced magnet moment of hydrogen nuclei (protons) contained within the fluid-filled pore space of porous media (reservoir rocks).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Unlike conventional logging measurements (e.g., acoustic, density, neutron, and resistivity), which respond to both the rock matrix and fluid properties and are strongly dependent on mineralogy, NMR-logging measurements respond to the presence of hydrogen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Because hydrogen atoms primarily occur in pore fluids, NMR effectively responds to the volume, composition, viscosity, and distribution of these fluids, for example oil, gas or water.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR logs provide information about the quantities of fluids present, the properties of these fluids, and the sizes of the pores containing these fluids.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The basic core and log measurement is the *T*2 decay, presented as a distribution of *T*2 amplitudes versus time at each sample depth, typically from 0.3 ms to 3 s.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The *T*2 decay is further processed to give the total pore volume (the total porosity) and pore volumes within different ranges of *T*2.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The most common volumes are the bound fluid and free fluid.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] A permeability estimate is made using a transform such as the Timur-Coates or SDR permeability transforms.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] By running the log with different acquisition parameters, direct hydrocarbon typing and enhanced diffusion are possible.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Real-time applications of NMR in liquid media have been developed using specifically designed flow probes (flow cell assemblies) which can replace standard tube probes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] This has enabled techniques that can incorporate the use of high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or other continuous flow sample introduction devices.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] These flow probes have used in various online process monitoring such as chemical reactions, environmental pollutant degradation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR has now entered the arena of real-time process control and process optimization in oil refineries and petrochemical plants.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Two different types of NMR analysis are utilized to provide real time analysis of feeds and products in order to control and optimize unit operations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Time-domain NMR (TD-NMR) spectrometers operating at low field (2–20 MHz for 1 H) yield free induction decay data that can be used to determine absolute hydrogen content values, rheological information, and component composition.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] These spectrometers are used in mining, polymer production, cosmetics and food manufacturing as well as coal analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] High resolution FT-NMR spectrometers operating in the 60 MHz range with shielded permanent magnet systems yield high resolution 1 H NMR spectra of refinery and petrochemical streams.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The variation observed in these spectra with changing physical and chemical properties is modeled using chemometrics to yield predictions on unknown samples.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] The prediction results are provided to control systems via analogue or digital outputs from the spectrometer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] In the Earth's magnetic field, NMR frequencies are in the audio frequency range, or the very low frequency and ultra low frequency bands of the radio frequency spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Earth's field NMR (EFNMR) is typically stimulated by applying a relatively strong dc magnetic field pulse to the sample and, after the end of the pulse, analyzing the resulting low frequency alternating magnetic field that occurs in the Earth's magnetic field due to free induction decay (FID).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] These effects are exploited in some types of magnetometers, EFNMR spectrometers, and MRI imagers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Their inexpensive portable nature makes these instruments valuable for field use and for teaching the principles of NMR and MRI.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] An important feature of EFNMR spectrometry compared with high-field NMR is that some aspects of molecular structure can be observed more clearly at low fields and low frequencies, whereas other aspects observable at high fields are not observable at low fields.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] In zero field NMR all magnetic fields are shielded such that magnetic fields below 1 nT (nanotesla) are achieved and the nuclear precession frequencies of all nuclei are close to zero and indistinguishable.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Under those circumstances the observed spectra are no-longer dictated by chemical shifts but primarily by *J*-coupling interactions which are independent of the external magnetic field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Since inductive detection schemes are not sensitive at very low frequencies, on the order of the *J*-couplings (typically between 0 and 1000 Hz), alternative detection schemes are used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Specifically, sensitive magnetometers turn out to be good detectors for zero field NMR.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] A zero magnetic field environment does not provide any polarization hence it is the combination of zero field NMR with hyperpolarization schemes that makes zero field NMR desirable.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR quantum computing uses the spin states of nuclei within molecules as qubits.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] NMR differs from other implementations of quantum computers in that it uses an ensemble of systems; in this case, molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Various magnetometers use NMR effects to measure magnetic fields, including proton precession magnetometers (PPM) (also known as proton magnetometers), and Overhauser magnetometers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] Surface magnetic resonance (or magnetic resonance sounding) is based on the principle of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and measurements can be used to indirectly estimate the water content of saturated and unsaturated zones in the earth's subsurface.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/nuclear-magnetic-resonance-p02] SNMR is used to estimate aquifer properties, including quantity of water contained in the aquifer, porosity, and hydraulic conductivity.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Time-resolved spectroscopy and infrared spectroscopy typically yield similar yet complementary information.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Electromagnetic radiation from the illuminated spot is collected with a lens.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Elastic scattered radiation at the wavelength corresponding to the laser line (Rayleigh scattering) is filtered out by either a notch filter, edge pass filter, or a band pass filter, while the rest of the collected light is dispersed onto a detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spontaneous Raman scattering is typically very weak.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As a result, for many years the main difficulty in collecting Raman spectra was separating the weak inelastically scattered light from the intense Rayleigh scattered laser light (referred to as "laser rejection").
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Historically, Raman spectrometers used holographic gratings and multiple dispersion stages to achieve a high degree of laser rejection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the past, photomultipliers were the detectors of choice for dispersive Raman setups, which resulted in long acquisition times.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, modern instrumentation almost universally employs notch or edge filters for laser rejection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Dispersive single-stage spectrographs (axial transmissive (AT) or Czerny–Turner (CT) monochromators) paired with CCD detectors are most common although Fourier transform (FT) spectrometers are also common for use with NIR lasers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The name "Raman spectroscopy" typically refers to vibrational Raman spectroscopy using laser wavelengths which are not absorbed by the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] There are many other variations of Raman spectroscopy including surface-enhanced Raman, resonance Raman, tip-enhanced Raman, polarized Raman, stimulated Raman, transmission Raman, spatially-offset Raman, and hyper Raman.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Although the inelastic scattering of light was predicted by Adolf Smekal in 1923, it was not observed in practice until 1928.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect was named after one of its discoverers, the Indian scientist C.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman, who observed the effect in organic liquids in 1928 together with K.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Krishnan, and independently by Grigory Landsberg and Leonid Mandelstam in inorganic crystals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman won the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1930 for this discovery.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The first observation of Raman spectra in gases was in 1929 by Franco Rasetti.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Systematic pioneering theory of the Raman effect was developed by Czechoslovak physicist George Placzek between 1930 and 1934.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The mercury arc became the principal light source, first with photographic detection and then with spectrophotometric detection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the years following its discovery, Raman spectroscopy was used to provide the first catalog of molecular vibrational frequencies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, the sample was held in a long tube and illuminated along its length with a beam of filtered monochromatic light generated by a gas discharge lamp.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The photons that were scattered by the sample were collected through an optical flat at the end of the tube.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To maximize the sensitivity, the sample was highly concentrated (1 M or more) and relatively large volumes (5 mL or more) were used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The magnitude of the Raman effect correlates with the polarizability of the electrons in a molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is a form of inelastic light scattering, where a photon excites the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This excitation puts the molecule into a virtual energy state for a short time before the photon is emitted.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Inelastic scattering means that the energy of the emitted photon is of either lower or higher energy than the incident photon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] After the scattering event, the sample is in a different rotational or vibrational state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For the total energy of the system to remain constant after the molecule moves to a new rovibronic (rotational–vibrational–electronic) state, the scattered photon shifts to a different energy, and therefore a different frequency.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This energy difference is equal to that between the initial and final rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is higher in energy than the initial state, the scattered photon will be shifted to a lower frequency (lower energy) so that the total energy remains the same.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This shift in frequency is called a Stokes shift, or downshift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is lower in energy, the scattered photon will be shifted to a higher frequency, which is called an anti-Stokes shift, or upshift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For a molecule to exhibit a Raman effect, there must be a change in its electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability with respect to the vibrational coordinate corresponding to the rovibronic state.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The intensity of the Raman scattering is proportional to this polarizability change.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the Raman spectrum (scattering intensity as a function of the frequency shifts) depends on the rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect is based on the interaction between the electron cloud of a sample and the external electric field of the monochromatic light, which can create an induced dipole moment within the molecule based on its polarizability.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because the laser light does not excite the molecule there can be no real transition between energy levels.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect should not be confused with emission (fluorescence or phosphorescence), where a molecule in an excited electronic state emits a photon and returns to the ground electronic state, in many cases to a vibrationally excited state on the ground electronic state potential energy surface.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering also contrasts with infrared (IR) absorption, where the energy of the absorbed photon matches the difference in energy between the initial and final rovibronic states.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The dependence of Raman on the electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability derivative also differs from IR spectroscopy, which depends on the electric dipole moment derivative, the atomic polar tensor (APT).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This contrasting feature allows rovibronic transitions that might not be active in IR to be analyzed using Raman spectroscopy, as exemplified by the rule of mutual exclusion in centrosymmetric molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Transitions which have large Raman intensities often have weak IR intensities and vice versa.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If a bond is strongly polarized, a small change in its length such as that which occurs during a vibration has only a small resultant effect on polarization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-O, N-O, O-H) are therefore, comparatively weak Raman scatterers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Such polarized bonds, however, carry their electrical charges during the vibrational motion, (unless neutralized by symmetry factors), and this results in a larger net dipole moment change during the vibration, producing a strong IR absorption band.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Conversely, relatively neutral bonds (e.g.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-C, C-H, C=C) suffer large changes in polarizability during a vibration.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the dipole moment is not similarly affected such that while vibrations involving predominantly this type of bond are strong Raman scatterers, they are weak in the IR.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A third vibrational spectroscopy technique, inelastic incoherent neutron scattering (IINS), can be used to determine the frequencies of vibrations in highly symmetric molecules that may be both IR and Raman inactive.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IINS selection rules, or allowed transitions, differ from those of IR and Raman, so the three techniques are complementary.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They all give the same frequency for a given vibrational transition, but the relative intensities provide different information due to the different types of interaction between the molecule and the incoming particles, photons for IR and Raman, and neutrons for IINS.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman shifts are typically reported in wavenumbers, which have units of inverse length, as this value is directly related to energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] where Δν̃ is the Raman shift expressed in wavenumber, λ0 is the excitation wavelength, and λ1 is the Raman spectrum wavelength.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Most commonly, the unit chosen for expressing wavenumber in Raman spectra is inverse centimeters (cm−1).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Modern Raman spectroscopy nearly always involves the use of lasers as excitation light sources.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because lasers were not available until more than three decades after the discovery of the effect, Raman and Krishnan used a mercury lamp and photographic plates to record spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Early spectra took hours or even days to acquire due to weak light sources, poor sensitivity of the detectors and the weak Raman scattering cross-sections of most materials.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various colored filters and chemical solutions were used to select certain wavelength regions for excitation and detection but the photographic spectra were still dominated by a broad center line corresponding to Rayleigh scattering of the excitation source.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Technological advances have made Raman spectroscopy much more sensitive, particularly since the 1980s.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common modern detectors are now charge-coupled devices (CCDs).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Photodiode arrays and photomultiplier tubes were common prior to the adoption of CCDs.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The advent of reliable, stable, inexpensive lasers with narrow bandwidths has also had an impact.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy requires a light source such as a laser.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resolution of the spectrum relies on the bandwidth of the laser source used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Generally shorter wavelength lasers give stronger Raman scattering due to the ν4 increase in Raman scattering cross-sections, but issues with sample degradation or fluorescence may result.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Continuous wave lasers are most common for normal Raman spectroscopy, but pulsed lasers may also be used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] These often have wider bandwidths than their CW counterparts but are very useful for other forms of Raman spectroscopy such as transient, time-resolved and resonance Raman.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattered light is typically collected and either dispersed by a spectrograph or used with an interferometer for detection by Fourier Transform (FT) methods.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In many cases commercially available FT-IR spectrometers can be modified to become FT-Raman spectrometers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In most cases, modern Raman spectrometers use array detectors such as CCDs.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various types of CCDs exist which are optimized for different wavelength ranges.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Intensified CCDs can be used for very weak signals and/or pulsed lasers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral range depends on the size of the CCD and the focal length of spectrograph used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It was once common to use monochromators coupled to photomultiplier tubes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In this case the monochromator would need to be moved in order to scan through a spectral range.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT–Raman is almost always used with NIR lasers and appropriate detectors must be used depending on the exciting wavelength.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Germanium or Indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs) detectors are commonly used.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is usually necessary to separate the Raman scattered light from the Rayleigh signal and reflected laser signal in order to collect high quality Raman spectra using a laser rejection filter.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Notch or long-pass optical filters are typically used for this purpose.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Before the advent of holographic filters it was common to use a triple-grating monochromator in subtractive mode to isolate the desired signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This may still be used to record very small Raman shifts as holographic filters typically reflect some of the low frequency bands in addition to the unshifted laser light.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, Volume hologram filters are becoming more common which allow shifts as low as 5 cm−1 to be observed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is used in chemistry to identify molecules and study chemical bonding and intramolecular bonds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because vibrational frequencies are specific to a molecule's chemical bonds and symmetry (the fingerprint region of organic molecules is in the wavenumber range 500–1,500 cm−1), Raman provides a fingerprint to identify molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, Raman and IR spectra were used to determine the vibrational frequencies of SiO, Si2O2, and Si3O3 on the basis of normal coordinate analyses.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman is also used to study the addition of a substrate to an enzyme.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid-state physics, Raman spectroscopy is used to characterize materials, measure temperature, and find the crystallographic orientation of a sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As with single molecules, a solid material can be identified by characteristic phonon modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Information on the population of a phonon mode is given by the ratio of the Stokes and anti-Stokes intensity of the spontaneous Raman signal.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy can also be used to observe other low frequency excitations of a solid, such as plasmons, magnons, and superconducting gap excitations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Distributed temperature sensing (DTS) uses the Raman-shifted backscatter from laser pulses to determine the temperature along optical fibers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The orientation of an anisotropic crystal can be found from the polarization of Raman-scattered light with respect to the crystal and the polarization of the laser light, if the crystal structure's point group is known.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In nanotechnology, a Raman microscope can be used to analyze nanowires to better understand their structures, and the radial breathing mode of carbon nanotubes is commonly used to evaluate their diameter.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman active fibers, such as aramid and carbon, have vibrational modes that show a shift in Raman frequency with applied stress.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polypropylene fibers exhibit similar shifts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid state chemistry and the bio-pharmaceutical industry, Raman spectroscopy can be used to not only identify active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs), but to identify their polymorphic forms, if more than one exist.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, the drug Cayston (aztreonam), marketed by Gilead Sciences for cystic fibrosis, can be identified and characterized by IR and Raman spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Using the correct polymorphic form in bio-pharmaceutical formulations is critical, since different forms have different physical properties, like solubility and melting point.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has a wide variety of applications in biology and medicine.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has helped confirm the existence of low-frequency phonons in proteins and DNA, promoting studies of low-frequency collective motion in proteins and DNA and their biological functions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman reporter molecules with olefin or alkyne moieties are being developed for tissue imaging with SERS-labeled antibodies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has also been used as a noninvasive technique for real-time, in situ biochemical characterization of wounds.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Multivariate analysis of Raman spectra has enabled development of a quantitative measure for wound healing progress.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spatially offset Raman spectroscopy (SORS), which is less sensitive to surface layers than conventional Raman, can be used to discover counterfeit drugs without opening their packaging, and to non-invasively study biological tissue.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A reason why Raman spectroscopy is useful in biological applications is because its results often do not face interference from water molecules, due to the fact that they have permanent dipole moments, and as a result, the Raman scattering cannot be picked up on.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This is a large advantage, specifically in biological applications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy also has a wide usage for studying biominerals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Lastly, Raman gas analyzers have many practical applications, including real-time monitoring of anesthetic and respiratory gas mixtures during surgery.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has been used in several research projects as a means to detect explosives from a safe distance using laser beams.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is being further developed so it could be used in the clinical setting.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman4Clinic is a European organization that is working on incorporating Raman Spectroscopy techniques in the medical field.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They are currently working on different projects, one of them being monitoring cancer using bodily fluids such as urine and blood samples which are easily accessible.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique would be less stressful on the patients than constantly having to take biopsies which are not always risk free.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In photovoltaics, Raman spectroscopy has gained more interest in the past few years demonstrating high efficacy in delivering important properties for such materials.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This includes optoelectronic and physicochemical properties such as open circuit voltage, efficiency, and crystalline structure.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This has been demonstrated with several photovoltaic technologies, including kesterite-based, CIGS devices, Monocrystalline silicon cells, and perovskites devices.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is an efficient and non-destructive way to investigate works of art and cultural heritage artifacts, in part because it is a non-invasive process which can be applied *in situ*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It can be used to analyze the corrosion products on the surfaces of artifacts (statues, pottery, etc.), which can lend insight into the corrosive environments experienced by the artifacts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resulting spectra can also be compared to the spectra of surfaces that are cleaned or intentionally corroded, which can aid in determining the authenticity of valuable historical artifacts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is capable of identifying individual pigments in paintings and their degradation products, which can provide insight into the working method of an artist in addition to aiding in authentication of paintings.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also gives information about the original state of the painting in cases where the pigments have degraded with age.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In addition to paintings and artifacts, Raman spectroscopy can be used to investigate the chemical composition of historical documents (such as the Book of Kells), which can provide insight about the social and economic conditions when they were created.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also offers a noninvasive way to determine the best method of preservation or conservation of such cultural heritage artifacts, by providing insight into the causes behind deterioration.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IRUG (Infrared and Raman Users Group) Spectral Database is a rigorously peer-reviewed online database of IR and Raman reference spectra for cultural heritage materials such as works of art, architecture, and archaeological artifacts.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The database is open for the general public to peruse, and includes interactive spectra for over a hundred different types of pigments and paints.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy offers several advantages for microscopic analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since it is a light scattering technique, specimens do not need to be fixed or sectioned.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectra can be collected from a very small volume (< 1 μm in diameter, < 10 μm in depth); these spectra allow the identification of species present in that volume.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Water does not generally interfere with Raman spectral analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Thus, Raman spectroscopy is suitable for the microscopic examination of minerals, materials such as polymers and ceramics, cells, proteins and forensic trace evidence.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A Raman microscope begins with a standard optical microscope, and adds an excitation laser, a monochromator or polychromator, and a sensitive detector (such as a charge-coupled device (CCD), or photomultiplier tube (PMT)).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT-Raman has also been used with microscopes, typically in combination with near-infrared (NIR) laser excitation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Ultraviolet microscopes and UV enhanced optics must be used when a UV laser source is used for Raman microspectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In *direct imaging* (also termed *global imaging* or *wide-field illumination*), the whole field of view is examined for light scattering integrated over a small range of wavenumbers (Raman shifts).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, a wavenumber characteristic for cholesterol could be used to record the distribution of cholesterol within a cell culture.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique is being used for the characterization of large-scale devices, mapping of different compounds and dynamics study.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has already been used for the characterization of graphene layers, J-aggregated dyes inside carbon nanotubes and multiple other 2D materials such as MoS2 and WSe2.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since the excitation beam is dispersed over the whole field of view, those measurements can be done without damaging the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common approach is *hyperspectral imaging* or *chemical imaging*, in which thousands of Raman spectra are acquired from all over the field of view by, for example, raster scanning of a focused laser beam through a sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The data can be used to generate images showing the location and amount of different components.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Having the full spectroscopic information available in every measurement spot has the advantage that several components can be mapped at the same time, including chemically similar and even polymorphic forms, which cannot be distinguished by detecting only one single wavenumber.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Furthermore, material properties such as stress and strain, crystal orientation, crystallinity and incorporation of foreign ions into crystal lattices (e.g., doping, solid solution series) can be determined from hyperspectral maps.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Taking the cell culture example, a hyperspectral image could show the distribution of cholesterol, as well as proteins, nucleic acids, and fatty acids.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Sophisticated signal- and image-processing techniques can be used to ignore the presence of water, culture media, buffers, and other interferences.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because a Raman microscope is a diffraction-limited system, its spatial resolution depends on the wavelength of light, the numerical aperture of the focusing element, and — in the case of confocal microscopy — on the diameter of the confocal aperture.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] When operated in the visible to near-infrared range, a Raman microscope can achieve lateral resolutions of approx.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] 1 μm down to 250 nm, depending on the wavelength and type of objective lens (e.g., air *vs.* water or oil immersion lenses).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The depth resolution (if not limited by the optical penetration depth of the sample) can range from 1–6 μm with the smallest confocal pinhole aperture to tens of micrometers when operated without a confocal pinhole.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Depending on the sample, the high laser power density due to microscopic focussing can have the benefit of enhanced photobleaching of molecules emitting interfering fluorescence.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the laser wavelength and laser power have to be carefully selected for each type of sample to avoid its degradation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Applications of Raman imaging range from materials sciences to biological studies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For each type of sample, the measurement parameters have to be individually optimized.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For that reason, modern Raman microscopes are often equipped with several lasers offering different wavelengths, a set of objective lenses, and neutral density filters for tuning of the laser power reaching the sample.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Selection of the laser wavelength mainly depends on optical properties of the sample and on the aim of the investigation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, Raman microscopy of biological and medical specimens is often performed using red to near-infrared excitation (e.g., 785 nm, or 1,064 nm wavelength).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Due to typically low absorbances of biological samples in this spectral range, the risk of damaging the specimen as well as autofluorescence emission are reduced, and high penetration depths into tissues can be achieved.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the intensity of Raman scattering at long wavelengths is low (owing to the ω4 dependence of Raman scattering intensity), leading to long acquisition times.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] On the other hand, resonance Raman imaging of single-cell algae at 532 nm (green) can specifically probe the carotenoid distribution within a cell by a using low laser power of ~5 μW and only 100 ms acquisition time.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering, specifically tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy, produces high resolution hyperspectral images of single molecules, atoms, and DNA.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering is polarization sensitive and can provide detailed information on symmetry of Raman active modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While conventional Raman spectroscopy identifies chemical composition, polarization effects on Raman spectra can reveal information on the orientation of molecules in single crystals and anisotropic materials, e.g. strained plastic sheets, as well as the symmetry of vibrational modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarization–dependent Raman spectroscopy uses (plane) polarized laser excitation from a polarizer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman scattered light collected is passed through a second polarizer (called the analyzer) before entering the detector.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The analyzer is oriented either parallel or perpendicular to the polarization of the laser.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spectra acquired with the analyzer set at both perpendicular and parallel to the excitation plane can be used to calculate the depolarization ratio.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically a polarization scrambler is placed between the analyzer and detector also.It is convenient in polarized Raman spectroscopy to describe the propagation and polarization directions using Porto's notation, described by and named after Brazilian physicist Sergio Pereira da Silva Porto.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For isotropic solutions, the Raman scattering from each mode either retains the polarization of the laser or becomes partly or fully depolarized.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the vibrational mode involved in the Raman scattering process is totally symmetric then the polarization of the Raman scattering will be the same as that of the incoming laser beam.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the case that the vibrational mode is not totally symmetric then the polarization will be lost (scrambled) partially or totally, which is referred to as depolarization.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Hence polarized Raman spectroscopy can provide detailed information as to the symmetry labels of vibrational modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the solid state, polarized Raman spectroscopy can be useful in the study of oriented samples such as single crystals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability of a vibrational mode is not equal along and across the bond.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the intensity of the Raman scattering will be different when the laser's polarization is along and orthogonal to a particular bond axis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This effect can provide information on the orientation of molecules with a single crystal or material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral information arising from this analysis is often used to understand macro-molecular orientation in crystal lattices, liquid crystals or polymer samples.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarization technique is useful in understanding the connections between molecular symmetry, Raman activity, and peaks in the corresponding Raman spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarized light in one direction only gives access to some Raman–active modes, but rotating the polarization gives access to other modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Each mode is separated according to its symmetry.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] When polarized light interacts with a molecule, it distorts the molecule which induces an equal and opposite effect in the plane-wave, causing it to be rotated by the difference between the orientation of the molecule and the angle of polarization of the light wave.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If ${\textstyle \rho \geq {\frac {3}{4}}}$ , then the vibrations at that frequency are *depolarized*; meaning they are not totally symmetric.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Resonance Raman selection rules can be explained by the Kramers–Heisenberg equation using the Albrecht A and B terms, as demonstrated.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability operator connecting the initial and final states expresses the transition polarizability as a matrix element, as a function of the incidence frequency ω0.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The directions x, y, and z in the molecular frame are represented by the Cartesian tensor ρ and σ here.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Analyzing Raman excitation patterns requires the use of this equation, which is a sum-over-states expression for polarizability.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This series of profiles illustrates the connection between a Raman active vibration's excitation frequency and intensity.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This method takes into account sums over Franck-Condon's active vibrational states and provides insight into electronic absorption and emission spectra.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Nevertheless, the work highlights a flaw in the sum-over-states method, especially for large molecules like visible chromophores, which are commonly studied in Raman spectroscopy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The difficulty arises from the potentially infinite number of intermediary steps needed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While lowering the sum at higher vibrational states can help tiny molecules get over this issue, larger molecules find it more challenging when there are more terms in the sum, particularly in the condensed phase when individual eigenstates cannot be resolved spectrally.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To overcome this, two substitute techniques that do not require adding eigenstates can be considered.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Among these two methods are available: the transform method. and Heller's time-dependent approach.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The goal of both approaches is to take into consideration the frequency-dependent Raman cross-section σR(ω0) of a particular normal mode.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] At least 25 variations of Raman spectroscopy have been developed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The usual purpose is to enhance the sensitivity (e.g., Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS)), to improve the spatial resolution (Raman microscopy), or to acquire very specific information (resonance Raman).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Terms such as *spontaneous Raman spectroscopy* or *normal Raman spectroscopy* summarize Raman spectroscopy techniques based on Raman scattering by using normal far-field optics as described above.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Variants of normal Raman spectroscopy exist with respect to excitation-detection geometries, combination with other techniques, use of special (polarizing) optics and specific choice of excitation wavelengths for resonance enhancement.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Enhancement of Raman scattering is achieved by local electric-field enhancement by optical near-field effects (e.g. localized surface plasmons).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman signal enhancements are achieved through non-linear optical effects, typically realized by mixing two or more wavelengths emitted by spatially and temporally synchronized pulsed lasers.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Morphologically Directed Raman Spectroscopy (MDRS) combines automated particle imaging and Raman microspectroscopy into a singular integrated platform in order to provide particle size, shape, and chemical identification.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Automated particle imaging determines the particle size and shape distributions of components within a blended sample from images of individual particles.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The information gathered from automated particle imaging is then utilized to direct the Raman spectroscopic analysis.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman spectroscopic analytical process is performed on a randomly selected subset of the particles, allowing chemical identification of the sample's multiple components.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Tens of thousands of particles can be imaged in a matter of minutes using the MDRS method, making the process ideal for forensic analysis and investigating counterfeit pharmaceuticals and subsequent adjudications.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where, $\alpha$ is the 3x3 polarizability tensor.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In the **double-harmonic approximations**, the potential energy is expanded to the **second order** near equilibrium (harmonic force fields), while polarizability, is truncated at **first order** in the normal coordinates.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In practice, $\alpha$ can be calculated through analytical methods or by employing the finite difference method for energy under small perturbations in $\mathbf {F}$ .
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where M is the diagonal matrix of atomic masses and L is the matrix of orthonormal eigenvectors (normal modes).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since the $\partial {\boldsymbol {\alpha }}/\partial \mathbf {R}$ is known from finite differences or gradient calculation, it will used to calculate $Q_{p}$ , and further to get the Raman activities.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since some thermodynamic calculations ignored in the harmonic approximation, DFT-calculated harmonic frequencies are systematically **too high**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] For example, the B3LYP/TZVP scaling factor is 0.965.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Before to calculating the static spectrum, the structure must be optimized to its lowest energy point using the same or an approximate DFT basis set/functional.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The mentioned static (harmonic) method also has been integrated into the Gaussian software as default, using the keyword Opt Freq=Raman to calculate.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The harmonic approximation methods ignore some non-harmonic calculations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] As an alternative, *ab initio* or machine-learned molecular-dynamics trajectories provide dynamic Raman spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] At each time step, the real-time polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ is calculated, from the isotropic and anisotropic components we mentioned as $\alpha _{\mathrm {iso} }(t)$ and $\alpha _{\mathrm {aniso} }(t)$ , there will obtained from dynamical trajectory.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This expression is derived from the angular momentum averaging of scattered lights from the random molecular orientations.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The factor 4/3 the iso/aniso probably contribution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The ratio show the information on the symmetry of the vibrational modes.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] So, from the time dependent polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ , the isotropic and anisotropic time series can be obtained.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Their autocorrelation functions are calculated, Fourier transformed, and finally combined using the rotational averaging method to generate the total Raman spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This polarizability-autocorrelation Fourier transform method naturally integrates anharmonic coupling, temperature broadening, and the polarization effects.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] It is providing a realistic description of Raman spectroscopy beyond the harmonic approximation.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In recent years, machine learning has become a powerful tool in Raman spectroscopy, enabling data-driven prediction and interpretation of spectral line characteristics.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Such as machine learned interatomic potential and generative model.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] A **spectral line** is a weaker or stronger region in an otherwise uniform and continuous spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] It may result from emission or absorption of light in a narrow frequency range, compared with the nearby frequencies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Spectral lines are often used to identify atoms and molecules.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] These "fingerprints" can be compared to the previously collected ones of atoms and molecules, and are thus used to identify the atomic and molecular components of stars and planets, which would otherwise be impossible.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Spectral lines are the result of interaction between a quantum system (usually atoms, but sometimes molecules or atomic nuclei) and a single photon.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] When a photon has about the right amount of energy (which is connected to its frequency) to allow a change in the energy state of the system (in the case of an atom this is usually an electron changing orbitals), the photon is absorbed.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Then the energy will be spontaneously re-emitted, either as one photon at the same frequency as the original one or in a cascade, where the sum of the energies of the photons emitted will be equal to the energy of the one absorbed (assuming the system returns to its original state).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] A spectral line may be observed either as an *emission line* or an *absorption line*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Which type of line is observed depends on the type of material and its temperature relative to another emission source.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] An absorption line is produced when photons from a hot, broad spectrum source pass through a cooler material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The intensity of light, over a narrow frequency range, is reduced due to absorption by the material and re-emission in random directions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] By contrast, a bright emission line is produced when photons from a hot material are detected, perhaps in the presence of a broad spectrum from a cooler source.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The intensity of light, over a narrow frequency range, is increased due to emission by the hot material.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Spectral lines are highly atom-specific, and can be used to identify the chemical composition of any medium.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Several elements, including helium, thallium, and caesium, were discovered by spectroscopic means.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Spectral lines also depend on the temperature and density of the material, so they are widely used to determine the physical composition and condition of distant stars and other celestial bodies.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Some of these data cannot be obtained or analyzed by other means, and so the field of spectroscopy has grown as astronomical and telescopic exploration has grown.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Depending on the material and its physical conditions, the energy of the involved photons can vary widely, with the spectral lines observed across the electromagnetic spectrum, from radio waves to gamma rays.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] In other cases, the lines are designated according to the level of ionization by adding a Roman numeral to the designation of the chemical element.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] More detailed designations usually include the line wavelength and may include a multiplet number (for atomic lines) or band designation (for molecular lines).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Many spectral lines of atomic hydrogen also have designations within their respective series, such as the Lyman series or Balmer series.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Originally all spectral lines were classified into series: the *principal series*, *sharp series*, and *diffuse series*.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] These series exist across atoms of all elements, and the patterns for all atoms are well-predicted by the Rydberg-Ritz formula.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] These series were later associated with suborbitals.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] There are a number of effects which control spectral line shape.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] A spectral line extends over a tiny spectral band with a nonzero range of frequencies, not a single frequency (i.e., a nonzero spectral width).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] In addition, its center may be shifted from its nominal central wavelength.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] There are several reasons for this broadening and shift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] These reasons may be divided into two general categories – broadening due to local conditions and broadening due to extended conditions.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Broadening due to local conditions is due to effects which hold in a small region around the emitting element, usually small enough to assure local thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Broadening due to extended conditions may result from changes to the spectral distribution of the radiation as it traverses its path to the observer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] It also may result from the combining of radiation from a number of regions which are far from each other.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The lifetime of excited states results in natural broadening, also known as lifetime broadening.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The uncertainty principle relates the lifetime of an excited state (due to spontaneous radiative decay or the Auger process) with the uncertainty of its energy.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Some authors use the term "radiative broadening" to refer specifically to the part of natural broadening caused by the spontaneous radiative decay.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] A short lifetime will have a large energy uncertainty and a broad emission.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] This broadening effect results in an unshifted Lorentzian profile.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The natural broadening can be experimentally altered only to the extent that decay rates can be artificially suppressed or enhanced.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The atoms in a gas which are emitting radiation will have a distribution of velocities.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Each photon emitted will be "red"- or "blue"-shifted by the Doppler effect depending on the velocity of the atom relative to the observer.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The higher the temperature of the gas, the wider the distribution of velocities in the gas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Since the spectral line is a combination of all of the emitted radiation, the higher the temperature of the gas, the broader the spectral line emitted from that gas.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] This broadening effect is described by a Gaussian profile and there is no associated shift.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The presence of nearby particles will affect the radiation emitted by an individual particle.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Certain types of broadening are the result of conditions over a large region of space rather than simply upon conditions that are local to the emitting particle.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Opacity broadening is an example of a non-local broadening mechanism.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Electromagnetic radiation emitted at a particular point in space can be reabsorbed as it travels through space.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The line is broadened because the photons at the line center have a greater reabsorption probability than the photons at the line wings.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Indeed, the reabsorption near the line center may be so great as to cause a **self reversal** in which the intensity at the center of the line is less than in the wings.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] This process is also sometimes called **self-absorption**.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Radiation emitted by a moving source is subject to Doppler shift due to a finite line-of-sight velocity projection.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] If different parts of the emitting body have different velocities (along the line of sight), the resulting line will be broadened, with the line width proportional to the width of the velocity distribution.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] For example, radiation emitted from a distant rotating body, such as a star, will be broadened due to the line-of-sight variations in velocity on opposite sides of the star (this effect usually referred to as rotational broadening).
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The greater the rate of rotation, the broader the line.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Another example is an imploding plasma shell in a Z-pinch.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Each of these mechanisms can act in isolation or in combination with others.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Assuming each effect is independent, the observed line profile is a convolution of the line profiles of each mechanism.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] For example, a combination of the thermal Doppler broadening and the impact pressure broadening yields a Voigt profile.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] However, the different line broadening mechanisms are not always independent.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] For example, the collisional effects and the motional Doppler shifts can act in a coherent manner, resulting under some conditions even in a collisional *narrowing*, known as the Dicke effect.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] The phrase "spectral lines", when not qualified, usually refers to lines having wavelengths in the visible band of the full electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Many spectral lines occur at wavelengths outside this range.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] At shorter wavelengths, which correspond to higher energies, ultraviolet spectral lines include the Lyman series of hydrogen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] At the much shorter wavelengths of X-rays, the lines are known as characteristic X-rays because they remain largely unchanged for a given chemical element, independent of their chemical environment.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] Longer wavelengths correspond to lower energies, where the infrared spectral lines include the Paschen series of hydrogen.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] At even longer wavelengths, the radio spectrum includes the 21-cm line used to detect neutral hydrogen throughout the cosmos.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectral-line] For each element, the following table shows the spectral lines which appear in the visible spectrum at 380-780 nm.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectroscopy] Historically, spectroscopy originated as the study of the wavelength dependence of the absorption by gas phase matter of visible light dispersed by a prism.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectroscopy] Current applications of spectroscopy include biomedical spectroscopy in the areas of tissue analysis and medical imaging.
[src:spectroscopy-physics/spectroscopy] Matter waves and acoustic waves can be considered forms of radiative energy, and recently gravitational waves have been associated with a spectral signature in the context of the Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory (LIGO).
